1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 (4. e3 Bxc3+ {Here this is a mistake in
my opinion. Let's clarify:} 5. bxc3 O-O 6. Bd3 d6 7. Ne2 e5 8. e4 c5 9. d5 {
Now Black would like to play ...f5. But with a knight on e2 instead of f3,
White can prevent this. For example} Nbd7 10. f3 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Yg2g4,Ye2g3]
White will play g4, Ng3, or Ng3 immediately, when Black is left without active
counterplay.}) 4... c5 {Although the line played in this game does not
represent our repertoire, this game serves as a wonderful example of how to
play against the doubled c-pawns in the Nimzo! Black managed to exchange all
the minor pieces except for the dark-squared bishop. Then he attacked the weak
pawns on the light squares!} ({As a reply to Nf3, we can already consider the
direct} 4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 d6 {followed by either ...e5, ...c5, or both!}) 5.
e3 Nc6 6. Bd3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 {This is the famous Hübner Variation.} 8. O-O
e5 {The point of Black's move order is quite deep: he develops the knight to
c6 before playing ...d6 and ...e5 to have ...Ne7 available in reply to d5. See
9.d5...} 9. Nd2 {this is a playable line..but here are some alternatives...
examined by a positional point of view} (9. d5 Ne7 {Next Black will castle and
prepare ...f5.} (9... Na5 $2 {WE NEVER PLAY ...Na5 UNLESS WE KNOW IT IS THEORY
or unless the c4 pawn is dropping by force!} 10. e4 h6 ({After} 10... O-O 11.
Bg5 {could be annoying.}) 11. Nd2 ({Even if White plays some random moves like
} 11. Re1 O-O 12. h3 {Black will not win the c4-pawn:} b6 13. Be3 Ba6 14. Nd2 {
The battle will soon break out on the kingside, when the knight on d2 and the
bishop on d3 are much more flexibly placed than the knight on a5 and the
bishop on a6.}) 11... O-O 12. Nb3 $14) 10. e4 (10. Qc2 O-O 11. Nh4 $4 {This
was played in a few games! White wants to control f5 and play f4, or g3 and f4.
However, here comes a tactical trick!} e4 $3 $19 {Black is winning by force
after this amazing move.} 12. Bxe4 (12. Be2 g5 $19 {[%csl Rh4]}) 12... Nxe4 13.
Qxe4 g5 $1 {White is losing a piece as after} 14. Nf3 Bf5 $19 {[%csl Re4]
White's queen gets trapped.}) 10... h6 {With this generally useful move, we
want to play ...Nh7 and ...f5 (after castling)} 11. Re1 O-O 12. Nd2 Nh7 13. f3
f5 14. exf5 (14. Qc2 $4 f4 $19 15. Rb1 g5 16. a4 Ng6 17. Nb3 Nf6 18. Bd2 h5 19.
a5 g4 20. a6 b6 21. Bf1 g3 22. h3 Nh4 23. Qd3 Nh7 24. Nc1 Rf7 25. Re2 Rg7 26.
Be1 Ng5) 14... Bxf5 15. Ne4 Nf6 16. Qc2 Qd7 17. Bd2 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4
Qf5 20. Re2 Qxe4 21. fxe4 Rf7 22. Rf2 Raf8 23. Raf1 Nc8 (23... Kh7 24. a4 Rxf2
25. Rxf2 Rxf2 26. Kxf2 a5 (26... Nc8 27. a5 a6 28. Ke3 b6 29. axb6 Nxb6 30. Kd3
a5 31. Bc1 a4 32. Ba3 Kg6))) (9. dxc5 dxc5 10. e4 Be6 11. Re1 h6 12. Bb2 O-O
13. Bf1 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Nd7) 9... O-O 10. d5 (10. Nb3 b6 11. Qe2 e4 12. Bc2 Bf5
13. h3 h5 (13... Bg6 14. f4 exf3 15. gxf3 Bxc2 16. Qxc2 Qd7) 14. Nd2 Re8) (10.
Ne4 Bf5 $1 11. Nxf6+ ({If White takes on c5} 11. Nxc5 $2 {, then} e4 {wins
material for Black.} 12. Nxb7 Qc7 13. Nxd6 Qxd6 $19) 11... Qxf6 12. e4 (12.
Bxf5 Qxf5 13. d5 Na5 14. Qe2 (14. Qa4 b6 15. f3 Qd3 (15... e4)) 14... e4 $1 (
14... Qe4) (14... b6 15. e4 Qc8)) 12... Bd7 13. d5 Ne7 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 Ng6
16. Bg3 Qe7) 10... Ne7 (10... Na5 $2 {As already pointed out in the line with
9.d5: WE NEVER PLAY ...Na5 UNLESS WE KNOW IT IS THEORY or unless the c4 pawn
is dropping by force!}) 11. f3 (11. e4 h6 (11... Ne8 12. Qc2 f5 13. exf5 Nxf5
14. Ne4 h6 15. f4) 12. Qc2 (12. Rb1 Nh7 13. f4 exf4 {If White plays f4, we
always must take it.} (13... Qc7 $2 14. f5 {Now Black is strategically lost.}
f6 15. Nf3 Bd7 16. g4 Rf7 17. h4 b6 18. Rb2 $5 {[%cal Yb2g2,Yg4g5,Yg2g5] White
has an attack like in the King's Indian, while Black has no counterplay at all.
}) 14. Rxf4 Ng6 $1 {Now we change our plan as the knight finds a great square
on e5.} 15. Rf1 Ne5 $15 {[%csl Ge5]}) 12... Nh7 13. Re1 (13. f4 {Again: if
White plays f4, we always must take it.} exf4 14. Rxf4 Ng6 15. Rf1 Ne5 $15 {
[%csl Ge5]}) ({If} 13. Rb1 {then} b6 {followed by ...f5.}) 13... f5 {Compared
to White playing f4, the threats are reversed: he has to take on f5 as
otherwise Black would play ...f4.} 14. exf5 (14. f3 $2 f4 {Computers of 20
years ago would evaluate this position as better for White, yet Black has
already a winning advantage! E.g.} 15. Re2 g5 16. Nf1 Ng6 17. h3 Nf6 18. a4 h5
$19 {[%cal Yg5g4] Compared to the King's Indian Defence, here White has no
play on the queenside as he has doubled pawns and cannot play b2-b4! White's
pair of bishops is a sorry sight, while Black's knights and the c8-bishop are
very active.}) 14... Bxf5 15. Ne4 Qd7 {Protecting everything, stabilizing the
position. Our general strategy is to exchange the minor pieces, except for
White's dark-squared bishop. For example} (15... Nf6 {allows} 16. Nxc5) 16. f3
Nf6 17. Bd2 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. fxe4 Nc8 $17 {[%csl Rc4,Gc8,Rd2][%cal Yc8b6]
In such a position our knight is much more useful than the white bishop - it
can attack c4.}) (11. f4 $2 exf4 12. exf4 (12. Rxf4 Ng6 $15 (12... Bd7 13. Rxf6
)) 12... Bf5 (12... Bd7 $2 13. f5) 13. Qc2 Qd7 14. h3 h5 15. Re1 g6 16. Bxf5
Qxf5 17. Qxf5 Nxf5 18. Nf3 Rfe8 19. Bd2 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Re8 21. Rxe8+ Nxe8 22.
Kf2 Nf6 23. Ke2 Nd7) 11... Bf5 $5 {An interesting move, provoking e4.} ({
I would say that} 11... h6 $1 {is even better - continuing with our plan.}) 12.
e4 Bd7 13. Qc2 Nh5 (13... Ne8 14. Re1 f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Ne4) 14. g3 f5 15.
exf5 {Even here White should take on f5 as ...f4 is a threat.} (15. Rf2 f4 16.
g4 {In spite of White having the pawn on g4 instead of g2, Black gets a strong
attack:} Nf6 17. Nf1 g5 18. h3 h5 $19 {Followed by ...Ng6. Sacrifices on g4
are in the air.}) 15... Bxf5 16. Ne4 h6 $1 {A necessary prophylactic move - we
should not allow Ng5. In general, we want to play ...Nf6 and start to exchange
pieces. Except for White's dark-squared bishop!} (16... Nf6 17. Ng5 $132) (
16... Qd7 17. Ng5 $132) 17. Bd2 (17. Rb1 b6 18. a4 Nf6 $15) (17. g4 Bxe4 18.
Bxe4 Nf4 $15) 17... Qd7 18. Rae1 Bh3 19. Rf2 Rf7 20. Qd1 Nf6 21. Be3 Nxe4 22.
Bxe4 Bf5 23. Qc2 Raf8 24. Ref1 Bxe4 25. Qxe4 Qf5 26. a4 $2 Qxe4 27. fxe4 Rxf2
28. Rxf2 Rxf2 29. Kxf2 a5 $1 $19 {[%csl Ra4,Re3,Ge7][%cal Ye7c8,Yc8b6,Yb6a4]
White's a4-pawn is doomed. Surprisingly, the strong Hungarian GM finds himself
in a lost position without a fight.} 30. Ke2 Nc8 31. Kd3 Nb6 32. h4 Nxa4 33.
Bc1 Nb6 34. g4 Kf7 35. Bd2 a4 36. Bc1 Kf6 37. Ba3 g5 38. h5 Ke7 39. Bc1 Nd7 40.
Ke2 Nf6 41. Kf3 Kd7 42. Bb2 Kc7 43. Ba3 Kb6 44. Bc1 Ka5 45. Ba3 b6 46. Bc1 a3
47. Bxa3 Ka4 48. Bc1 0-1

