1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 h6 6. Bh4 d6 7. Bg3 Qe7 8.
e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 e5 10. Rb1 O-O 11. Ne2 c5 12. d5 Re8 (12... e4 13. Bc2 Ne5 $17 {
[%csl Rc2,Rc3,Rc4,Ge5] was maybe even better.}) 13. Bc2 Nf8 14. e4 {Black is
better in this closed position - the knights are stronger than the bishops.}
Rb8 ({After} 14... Ng6 15. O-O Nh5 16. f3 {Black's only problem is that ...f5
is not possible yet. However, it can be prepared.} Rf8 17. Qd2 f5 $15) 15. O-O
g5 $3 $17 {The center is closed - so a flank attack with ...g5-Ng6 is
positionally justified!} 16. h3 Ng6 17. Qd2 Kh7 {I am preparing my attack.} 18.
Rb2 b6 19. Rfb1 Bd7 ({Black can prevent a4-a5 by playing} 19... Qd8 {with the
idea} 20. a4 a5 $15 {[%cal Ye8g8,Yg6f4] Black's rook and queen are tied to the
defence of the b6-pawn, but on the other hand, White's rooks are neutralized.
He cannot put more pressure on b6, while Black's attack on the kingside is
about to start.}) 20. a4 {White does not find any other plan than a4-a5. This
is usually not a problem for Black.} Qf8 21. a5 bxa5 {I happily take the pawn.}
22. Rxb8 Rxb8 23. Rxb8 Qxb8 24. Qc1 Qb6 {Now I adjust my plan and will play an
endgame with an extra pawn.} 25. f3 Kg7 26. Qa3 Ne8 27. Nc1 Nc7 28. Nb3 a4 29.
Nc1 Na8 30. Bxa4 {White blunders, but his position was already lost.} ({
For example} 30. Nd3 Qa6 {Vacating the b6-square for the knight.} 31. Nb2 Nb6
32. Bd3 Qc8 33. Bf2 Nf4 $19) 30... Qa5 $19 0-1

