{Black was close to winning this typical endgame with the weak c-pawns. Study
this instructive game carefully!!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5.
Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 ({If White plays} 10.
Bg5 {then Black has different options:} cxd4 ({or} 10... h6 11. Bh4 $6 (11.
Bxf6 $142 Qxf6 12. d5 Ne7 $15) 11... cxd4 $1 12. cxd4 Bg4 $1 {Now this is even
stronger.} 13. d5 Nd4 14. Be2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 g5 16. Bg3 Rc8 $17 {[%csl Gd4,Rf3,
Rg3]}) ({If we play} 10... Bg4 {then White can play} 11. d5 {when we no longer
can play ...Ne7.}) 11. cxd4 Bg4 (11... exd4 {Taking the pawn is also fine, as
White has no easy way to regain it.} 12. Bc2 Bg4 $15) 12. d5 Nd4 $15) 10... Ne7
11. Nh4 {White fights against ...f5.} h6 {Interesting, but Black also had
other options.} 12. f4 {This is very similar to the famous game
Spassky-Fischer, Reykjavik 1972.} Ng6 $1 13. Nxg6 fxg6 {Since the game of
Fischer, this structure is known to be fine for Black.} 14. Rb1 b6 15. Rb2 Rb8
16. Qe1 Qe8 17. Qh4 Rb7 18. h3 Rbf7 19. Qg3 Nh5 20. Qxg6 {Now a forcing
sequence leads us into an endgame with just minor pieces:} Rxf4 21. Qxe8 Rxf1+
22. Bxf1 Rxe8 23. Rf2 Rf8 24. Rxf8+ Kxf8 {Black is the only one with winning
chances. The important question is, whether the position can be won. If Black
manages to play ...Ba6 and to transfer the knight to a5 the c4-pawn would be
lost.} 25. Kf2 Ke7 26. Kf3 Nf6 27. Ke3 Bd7 ({We will explore the continuation} 
27... Ba6 {a bit deeper.} 28. Be2 Nh7 29. Bd2 Ng5 30. Kd3 Nf7 31. Be1 (31. a3
$6 {This move will not be played in a game. It is however interesting to check,
if Black can win the position with the pawn on a3 since this structure is
often reached via the system 4.a3...} Nd8 32. Bd1 Nb7 33. Bb3 Na5 34. Ba2 Bc8
35. Be1 Bd7 36. Bf2 Ba4 37. Bh4+ g5 38. Be1 Bb3 39. Bxb3 Nxb3 40. h4 {White
holds after this.} (40. g4 $6 {Let's check if we can win if the white g-pawn
is on g4:} Kf6 41. Bd2 Kg6 42. Be1 h5 $3 43. Bf2 h4 $1 $19 {This endgame seems
to be winning for Black! The plan is ...Ng6-Nf4 and if White takes, we get a
winning pawn endgame.} 44. Be3 Na5 45. Bc1 Kf6 46. Be3 Nb7 47. Bc1 Nd8 48. Ke2
Nf7 49. Kf3 {To protect h3, the king has to go to h2.} Nh8 50. Kg2 Ng6 51. Kh2
Nf4 52. Bd2 Nd3 {But now c4 cannot be saved.} 53. Kg2 Nb2 $19) 40... Kf6 41. h5
Na5 42. Bd2 $11) 31... Nd8 32. Bd1 Nb7 33. Bb3 Na5 {White just manages to
defend.}) 28. Be2 {Black tried for a long time to win this endgame, though in
the end White held the draw.} Be8 29. Bd1 Nh7 30. Bd2 Ng5 31. Be1 Nf7 32. Kd3
Nd8 33. Bh4+ g5 34. Be1 Bd7 35. h4 Nb7 36. Bf2 Na5 37. Bb3 Kf6 38. Be1 Kg6 39.
Bf2 Be8 40. Be1 Bd7 41. Bf2 Nxb3 42. axb3 a5 43. hxg5 Kxg5 44. Be3+ Kg6 45. Bf2
Kh5 46. Be3 Bc8 47. Ke2 Bg4+ 48. Kd2 Kg6 49. Bf2 Kg5 50. Be3+ Kh5 51. Bf2 Bd7
52. Be3 Bc8 53. Ke2 Kg6 54. Bf2 Kf7 55. Be3 h5 56. Bg5 Ke8 57. Ke3 Kd7 58. Bh4
Kc7 59. Be7 Bd7 60. Kd3 Bg4 61. Kd2 Kd7 62. Bg5 Ke8 63. Bh4 Bd7 64. Bg5 a4 65.
bxa4 Bxa4 66. Bh4 Bb3 67. Kd3 Ba2 68. Bg5 Bb1+ 69. Ke3 1/2-1/2

