{In this blitz game, Black played very passively, mixing various strategies.
As a result, he was left without pawn brakes and had to wait passively for the
end!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 O-O 7. e4 d6
8. Bd3 e5 9. d5 Nbd7 10. Ne2 {Here White is better since he can develop his
knight to e2 and prevent Black's counterplay with ...f5.} Ne8 11. h4 {White is
going to play g4 next. The immediate g4 may have been answered with ...Qh4+.}
Nb6 12. g4 Qd7 13. a4 $1 {Black was cunningly threatening ...Qa4, either
forcing the exchange of queens or winning c4. Now he is left without
counterplay.} Qe7 14. Ng3 Bd7 15. a5 Nc8 16. Ra2 $1 {The rook is coming to g2.}
Rb8 17. Nf5 Qd8 18. g5 b5 19. cxb5 Bxb5 20. c4 Bd7 21. h5 Bxf5 22. exf5 f6 23.
h6 $1 $18 {White opens up the kingside and gets a winning attack.} fxg5 24.
hxg7 Rf7 25. f6 Nxf6 26. Bxg5 Rxg7 27. Bxh7+ Rxh7 28. Rxh7 Kxh7 29. Qd3+ e4 30.
fxe4 Qe7 31. e5+ Kg8 32. Bxf6 1-0

