{A very well-played game by Black - until the point where he blundered the e5
pawn!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 b6 7. O-O Bxc3
8. bxc3 Bb7 {This position is surprisingly good for White if it is played
properly.} 9. Qe2 ({The best move is} 9. Ne1 {preparing f3 to control the
important e4-square.}) 9... Ne4 10. Bb2 {This is a mistake in my opinion.} ({
The best move is again} 10. Ne1 {[%cal Yf2f3] with the idea that} Nxc3 $2 {
is met with} 11. Qc2 $18) 10... f5 11. Nd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 d6 13. f3 Nd7 14. e4
f4 $1 {Closing the position.} 15. Rad1 ({The pawn sacrifice} 15. e5 {is
interesting but not fully sufficient.} dxe5 $15) 15... e5 $1 16. Bc2 Bc6 $3 $17
{Black manages to stabilize the position, covering d7 and preventing Ba4.} (
16... Rf6 {is insufficient due to} 17. Ba4) 17. dxc5 dxc5 18. Qe2 (18. Qd6 {
can be answered with} Rf6 ({Even if we had to play a passive move like} 18...
Rc8 {White cannot pose problems since he effectively playing without his
bishops:} 19. Rd2 Qe8 20. Rfd1 Rf6 21. Qd3 Qe7 $17 {Black easily managed to
beat off White's attack on the d-file, since all his pieces are playing.}))
18... Qc7 19. Rd5 $5 {Having a strategically lost position, White tries to
complicate matters. Taking on d5 is still winning for Black though the
character of the game changes. It's also possible to ignore the rook.} Nf6 20.
Rfd1 Rad8 21. R1d2 Bxd5 22. cxd5 Ne8 {Finally Black took the exchange,
intending to block the d-pawn with ...Nd6.} 23. c4 Nd6 $4 {A terrible mistake.}
({Black had to play} 23... Qe7 $19 {first.} 24. Ba4 Nd6 $19 25. Bc6 {Now Black
can start attacking on the kingside:} g5 {[%cal Yg8h8,Yf8g8,Yg5g4]} ({or} 25...
Rf6 {[%cal Yf6h6,Ye7h4]})) 24. Bxe5 $18 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5,Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ye4e5]
Now White is winning.} Qe7 25. Bxd6 Rxd6 26. e5 Rh6 27. d6 Qh4 28. h3 Qg5 29.
e6 Rxh3 30. e7 1-0

