{This is a famous game which perfectly demonstrates, that the knight is
usually badly placed on a5! Black did not win the c4 pawn and his knight
turned out to be too far away from the action!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. e4 Ne8 11.
Be3 d6 12. O-O Na5 13. Ng3 Rc8 $2 {This is a big mistake! Now White has the
chance to protect his c4-pawn and to start an attack on the kingside.} 14. d5
$1 {Closes the c-file. Now the c4-pawn can only be attacked once more by ...
Ba6, but White can always defend it with Qe2.} e5 15. f4 $3 $16 {This move is
very good, since his opponents knights are too far away from e5.} Rc7 (15...
exf4 16. Bxf4 Nf6 $2 17. Bg5 $18) 16. f5 $18 {We are already familiar with
this strategy. White gains a lot of space and is going to attack on the
kingside with superior forces.} f6 17. Qe2 Bc8 18. h4 Rb7 19. Rf2 Bd7 20. a4
Nc7 21. Nf1 {Preparing g4.} Qe8 22. Bc2 h6 23. g4 Kf7 24. g5 hxg5 25. hxg5 Ke7
26. Rh2 Rh8 27. Nd2 Rb8 28. Rxh8 Qxh8 29. Kg2 Rf8 30. Rh1 Qg8 31. g6 {White
wins due to his tremendous space advantage.} Kd8 32. Nf1 Re8 33. Rh7 Qf8 34.
Ng3 Qe7 35. Nh5 Rg8 36. Bh6 Ne8 37. Kf2 Qf8 38. Bd3 Bxa4 39. Qe3 Bd1 40. Nxg7
Nxg7 41. Bxg7 Qe8 42. Bxf6+ Kc8 43. Qh6 Ba4 44. Re7 1-0

