{An instructive game with a successful light-square strategy, coming from a
different opening!} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 Bc5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e3 a6 6. Nf3 Nf6
7. d4 Bb4 8. Qc2 O-O 9. O-O Bxc3 {Black immediately goes for a light-square
strategy - this is best!} (9... Rb8 {A random move just to demonstrate the
following point.} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Rb1 {(another random move)} Bxc3 12. Qxc3
e4 {Now this strategy does not work: after the exchange on e5, things are
different since after ...e4 the a1-h8 diagonal is open for White's
dark-squared bishop.} 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. b4 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Yc1b2]}) 10. Qxc3 e4
{White's pawn structure is more healthy than in the previous example. Still,
this plan works for Black.} 11. Nd2 Bf5 12. f3 {Exchanging the strong e4-pawn,
but creating weaknesses.} ({If White does not play f3 and goes for something
like} 12. a3 {, intending b4, we can see two types of light-square strategy.
We are not trying to find the best moves but rather describe Black's plans:} d5
(12... Ne7 13. b3 c6 {This is the other strategy: Black intends to play ...d5
and take back on d5 with a pawn.} 14. Bb2 d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Qc1 Qd7 17. a4
Nc6 18. Ba3 Rfe8 ({or} 18... Rfc8) 19. Qb2 {Now we can start attacking; for
example} Bh3 20. Rac1 Nd8 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yd8e6,Ye6g5] A nice idea - the
knight goes to g5 and targets the weak squares on h3 and f3.}) 13. cxd5 Ne7 14.
b4 Nexd5 {Here we take on d5 with a piece.} 15. Qc2 Re8 16. Bb2 Qd7 17. Rac1
Bh3 18. Rfe1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 h5 {[%csl Gd5,Gd7,Ge6,Ge8,Gf5][%cal Yd7f5,Ye8e6]
Black's whole play is taking place on the light squares!}) 12... exf3 13. Bxf3
Bh3 14. Re1 h5 (14... Ng4 $5 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Gd8,Gg4,Gh3][%cal Yf7f5,Yd8f6,
Yc6d8,Yd8e6,Ye6g5] was probably an even better way to exploit White's
weaknesses.}) 15. e4 h4 16. Nf1 Nh7 $15 17. Bf4 Qf6 18. Rad1 Ng5 19. Bh1 Bg4
20. Bxg5 Qxg5 21. Rd2 f5 22. exf5 Bxf5 23. Qe3 Qh5 24. gxh4 Qxh4 25. Qg3 Qh6
26. Bd5+ Kh8 27. Bxc6 bxc6 28. Rf2 Rf6 29. Qe3 Qg6+ 30. Ng3 Re6 31. Qd2 Rxe1+
32. Qxe1 Re8 33. Qd1 Bg4 34. Qf1 Re3 35. Rf4 Kg8 36. b3 Re8 37. h3 Bd7 38. Kh2
Qh6 39. Rf2 Qh4 40. Rf4 Qh6 41. Rf2 Qh4 42. Rf4 1/2-1/2

