{Another great game with the light-square strategy!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Nbd7 7. g3 a5 8. Bg2 $6 ({White should have
prevented ...a4 by playing} 8. b3 a4 $140 $2 9. b4 $16 {[%csl Ra4]}) 8... a4 $1
9. Nf3 Qe7 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 e5 12. e3 $2 {A strategically terrible move!}
Re8 13. Bd2 e4 $1 $17 14. Ne1 b6 15. Bc3 Bb7 16. Bh3 (16. d5 {Stopping ...d5,
but giving away the c5-square. Here we see that it's very useful to have our
pawn on a4!} Nc5 $17 {[%csl Gc5]}) 16... d5 17. Ng2 ({If} 17. cxd5 {then for
example} Nxd5 18. Ng2 N7f6 19. Rac1 Bc8 ({or} 19... Ba6) 20. Bxc8 Rexc8 21. Bb4
{We are never interested in taking this bishop and will play around it. We are
going to win on the kingside.} Qe6 $17 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Ge6,Gf6][%cal Ye6h3] If
necessary, we can even stabilize our position with ...c6 - White has no play
at all.}) 17... Ba6 $19 18. Nf4 Bxc4 19. Rfe1 Nf8 20. Bb4 Qd8 21. Rac1 Ng6 22.
Nxg6 hxg6 23. Bf1 b5 24. Bxc4 {We can see that White's dark-squared bishop is
totally passive! A common result of a successful light-square strategy!} bxc4
25. Bc3 Qd7 26. Qe2 g5 27. Kg2 g4 28. Rh1 g6 29. h3 gxh3+ 30. Rxh3 Kg7 31. Rch1
Rh8 32. f3 Rxh3 33. Rxh3 Rh8 34. Rxh8 Kxh8 35. f4 Kg7 36. Qd1 Ng4 37. Bd2 Nf6
38. Bc3 Qg4 39. Qxg4 Nxg4 40. Bd2 Kh6 41. Kf1 Kh5 42. Kg2 c6 43. Bc1 c3 44.
bxc3 Nh6 45. Kh3 f5 46. Bd2 Nf7 47. Bc1 Nd6 48. Bd2 Nc4 49. Bc1 g5 50. fxg5
Kxg5 51. Kh2 Na5 52. Kh3 Nb3 53. Bb2 Kh5 54. Kh2 Kg4 55. Kg2 Nd2 56. Kf2 Nc4
57. Bc1 Kh3 0-1

