{And another perfect example of a light-square strategy:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 d6 5. g3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nbd7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Rb1 Rb8 10.
a4 b6 11. Ba3 Bb7 12. a5 Qe7 13. Qa4 e5 14. e3 {Again this dubious move!} Be4
15. Rb2 h6 {Black has a stable advantage.} 16. Nd2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 c5 $1 $17 {
Killing the a3-bishop. The weakness on b6 is not felt, as it is securely
protected.} 18. Qc2 ({Stopping ...e4 with} 18. e4 exd4 19. cxd4 cxd4 {loses a
pawn.}) 18... e4 $1 19. Rbb1 Qe6 {Provoking d5 and targeting the weak light
squares on the kingside.} 20. Rbe1 Re7 (20... Nf8 $1 {[%csl Gf8,Gg5][%cal
Yf8h7,Yh7g5]} 21. Re2 (21. f3) 21... N8h7 22. h4 {Preventing ...Ng5 but
weakening other squares. For example} Ng4 (22... g5) 23. Rfe1 f5 24. Qc1 Nhf6
25. d5 Qd7) (20... Nh7 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Yh7g5]}) 21. f3 exf3+ 22. Nxf3 Rbe8
(22... Qxc4 $19) 23. axb6 axb6 24. Qb3 Qe4 $19 (24... Ne4 $19) 25. Kg1 Qd3 26.
Bc1 Ne4 27. Rd1 Qxc3 28. Qb5 Nef6 29. dxc5 dxc5 30. Bb2 Qxe3+ 31. Kh1 Qe4 32.
Rde1 Qb7 33. Rxe7 Rxe7 34. Kg2 Ng4 35. Kh3 h5 36. Bc1 Re2 37. Kh4 Qe4 38. Bf4
Qe7+ 39. Bg5 f6 40. Kxh5 Nxh2 41. Bf4 Nxf1 42. Qc6 Qf7+ 43. Kh4 Ne3 44. Qc8+
Nf8 45. Qb8 Ng2+ 46. Kh3 Qh5+ 0-1

