{In the following games we see Black occupy the important e4-square with
either a knight or the bishop. We will clarify in which situations it is
effective to put a knight on e4 (possibly in connection with active play on
the kingside with ...f5, ...Rf6, etc), and in which positions this important
central square is better suited for our light-squared bishop.}  *

[Event "ICC blitz game"]
[Site "Marianske Lazne"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "GM Player"]
[Black "Kelires"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "E14"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "68"]
[EventDate "2010.01.16"]
[EventType "swiss"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "CZE"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8.
b4 d6 9. Bb2 Ne4 {Such a position is very typical for the Nimzo-Indian 
(despite the fact the it was reached via the Bogo-Indian). A general rule: if
White plays e3 in such a position, we play ...Ne4 and ...f5. If White develops
with g3 and Bg2, we play ...Be4.} 10. Qc2 a5 11. b5 Nd7 12. Be2 f5 13. O-O Rf6
{We want to transfer the rook to g6 or h6. Playing ....Ndf6 would be
ineffective.} 14. c5 (14. d5 Rh6 (14... e5 15. Nh4 $1)) ({A possible
continuation of the attack after} 14. Ne1 Rh6 $1 {(compare the game)} 15. f3
Qh4 16. fxe4 Qxh2+ 17. Kf2 fxe4 18. Bd1 Rf8+ 19. Ke2 Rxf1 20. Kxf1 Rf6+ 21. Ke2
Qh5+ 22. Kd2 Rf2+ $19) 14... Bd5 15. c6 {Closing the queenside is pointless
since Black is playing on the kingside and White no longer has any play on the
queenside.} ({Better was} 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Rac1 {Black has to adjust his plan:
} Rf8 $1 $11 {with the idea} (16... Rh6 {is strongly answered by} 17. Qc7 $14)
17. Qc7 Rc8 $15) 15... Nf8 16. Ne1 (16. Nd2 Rg6 $1 {Black's attack is very
dangerous. For instance} 17. g3 h5 $1 {Black has other ideas, but this is
connected with a nice idea:} 18. Bxh5 Qg5 $1 19. Bxg6 Nxd2 20. Qxd2 Bf3 $1 $17
{White can hardly defend against Black's mating threats on the light squares.})
16... Rh6 $1 {Since the knight protects g2, we are going to attack h2.} 17. g3
{Preventing ...Qh4, but Black now had an amazing idea:} Ng5 (17... Nd2 $3 $19
18. Qxd2 Qh4 $1 {After sacrificing the knight, Black sacrifices the queen.
White must suffer heavy material losses to avoid checkmate.} 19. gxh4 Rg6+ 20.
Ng2 Rxg2+ 21. Kh1 Rxf2+ 22. Kg1 (22. Bf3 Bxf3+ 23. Kg1 Rxd2 24. Rxf3 Rxb2 $19)
22... Rg2+ $19) 18. f3 Ng6 19. Bd3 Nh3+ 20. Kh1 f4 21. gxf4 a4 22. Ng2 Nh4 23.
Qe2 Qe7 (23... Nf5 $3 $17 24. Bxf5 exf5) 24. Rae1 Rf8 (24... Nf5 $1 $17) 25.
Bc1 Bb3 26. Bd2 Qf7 27. Nxh4 Rxh4 28. Qg2 Qh5 29. Re2 Rf6 30. Be1 $2 Rhxf4 $3
$19 31. exf4 Nxf4 32. Qg4 $2 Qxg4 33. fxg4 Bd5+ 34. Be4 Nxe2 0-1

