1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 {The line with 4.Qc2 is also known as the
Classical System. White plays in a positionally well-founded manner: he
prevents the doubling of his c-pawns and controls the important e4-square.} d6
$5 {A very interesting variation for Black, with practically zero theory.
White has a huge number of set-ups, and against each one of them, we have
several good options! Our next move is in most cases going to be ...Nbd7. Then
we will decide whether to develop the c8-bishop with ...b6-Bb7 or with a
well-timed ...e6-e5. We always keep in mind a possible light-square strategy!
THE LINES THAT FOLLOW NOW, SHOULD NOT BE MEMORIZED! WE JUST HAVE TO TRY TO
UNDERSTAND THE TYPICAL PLANS AND IDEAS!} 5. a3 (5. Nf3 $5 Nbd7 $5 6. a3 $5 (6.
g3 b6 (6... O-O 7. Bg2 e5 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 e4 $1 {Here we can go for a
light-square strategy.} (9... Re8 {gives White the chance to play} 10. dxe5 $14
) 10. Nd2 Re8 11. O-O (11. Nf1 h6 {We should consider this; not allowing Bg5.}
(11... d5 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Ne3 Be6 $15) 12. Ne3 c6 13. O-O {
A common idea is} Nb6 14. b3 d5 15. c5 Nbd7 {White has won some time, but on
the other hand, has taken off the pressure from d5.} 16. Bb2 Nf8 {[%cal Yf8h7,
Yh7g5,Yc8h3]} 17. b4 {Should we at any point include ...a6 or not? In general,
we should only play ...a6 if we can significantly delay b4-b5 (or can prevent
it altogether). Here it can be interesting:} a6 18. a4 (18. Rac1 N8h7 {[%cal
Yh7g5]} 19. h4 {In this way, White can only prevent ...Ng5 for one move.} g5
20. hxg5 Nxg5 {h4 has made matters worse for White - the opening of lines on
the kingside is in Black's favour.}) 18... Bd7 {We stop b5 for the time being.}
) 11... d5 12. cxd5 Nb6 $1 13. Qc2 Bf5 {Here Black is already better. If White
plays f3, we happily take it and if something like} 14. e3 Nbxd5 15. Nc4 {
is played, then} Qc8 {[%cal Yf5h3,Yh7h5,Yh5h4] is a very good move.}) (6... e5
{--> see model game 0-1 (32) Gasanov,E (2484)-Kovalenko,I (2657) Zalakaros
2017.}) 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O O-O 9. a3 (9. Nd1 {With the idea of trapping the
b4-bishop, can be answered with} d5 10. c5 bxc5 11. a3 Ba5 12. dxc5 c6 13. b4
Bc7 {The b7-bishop does not look so well right now, but it can later move to
a6. Black can also start pushing his e-pawn with ...e6-e5.}) 9... Bxc3 10. Qxc3
a5 {[%cal Ya5a4]} 11. b3 Be4 $1 {We already know from the "Typical Strategies"
lesson that this is a good square for our bishop. Why do we hurry to put it
there? If we play some random moves, White will soon (after Bb2) be ready for
d4-d5, which would be very strong with our bishop on b7. We can get similar
positions also from the Bogo- or the Queen's Indian.} 12. Bb2 c6 {This is my
favourite plan: Black is going for either ...b5 or ...d5.} ({or} 12... Qb8 $5
13. Nd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qb7+ {Giving this check makes sense, as} (14... b5 $5) (
14... c5) (14... d5) 15. f3 {creates long-term weaknesses.} d5 {Black has a
good game.})) (6. e4 e5 $1 $132 ({or} 6... c5 $1)) (6. Bd2 $5 {An important
thing to remember: against the set-up with Qc2-Bd2 we must go for ...Nbd7 and .
..c5!} c5 $1 (6... O-O {--> see model game 0-1 (33) Jacimovic,D (2400)
-Papaioannou,I (2645) Kupelo.}) 7. a3 (7. Nb5 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Ne4 $1 {is fine
for Black, e.g.} 9. Qf4 Qa5+ 10. Nd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Ke7 $36) 7...
Bxc3 8. Bxc3 O-O 9. e3 (9. e4 $6 cxd4 $1 10. Bxd4 e5 $1 11. Bc3 Nc5 12. Nd2 Bd7
$3 $15 13. b3 (13. b4 Na4) 13... Bc6 $1 {Black has no time to pressurize our
pawn on d6.} 14. f3 a5 15. Be2 Qb6 $17) (9. dxc5 Nxc5 $36 10. Ng5 $6 (10. g3 $6
{leads us back to 0-1 (33) Jacimovic,D (2400)-Papaioannou,I (2645) Kupelo, by
transposition.}) 10... e5) 9... b6 $3 10. Be2 (10. Bd3 Bb7 $1 11. O-O (11. dxc5
$6 Nxc5 $3 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Bxh7+ Kh8 14. Bd3 Qxb2 $1 $17) 11... Bxf3 $3 12.
gxf3 cxd4 $1 13. exd4 $2 (13. Bxd4 Rc8 $132) 13... Rc8 $1 $17 (13... Re8 $5 {
with the idea of transferring the knight to g6:} 14. Kh1 Nf8 15. Rg1 Ng6 {
[%cal Yf6h5]}) 14. Kh1 d5 15. b3 g6 16. Rg1 Nh5 17. Qd2 Qf6 $17) (10. dxc5 Nxc5
11. Be2 (11. Ng5 e5) 11... Bb7 (11... Nce4 $5 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 $11) 12. O-O Rc8
$132) 10... Bb7 11. O-O Ne4 (11... Rc8 $5 $132) (11... Qe7 12. Rfd1 Rac8 13.
dxc5 Nxc5 $1 {This is perfectly possible as taking on f6 turns out to be
favourable for Black:} (13... bxc5 14. Nd2 $5) ({For sure, we don't go for the
symmetrical position.} 13... dxc5 14. Nd2 $16) 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Rxd6 $2 Be4 $1
16. Qc3 Qxc3 17. bxc3 $15 {Black has more than enough compensation for the
pawn.}) 12. Be1 f5 $132) (6. e3 O-O (6... b6) (6... e5) 7. Bd3 e5 {Since White
is ready to play e4, I like ...e5 more than ...b6.} 8. O-O Bxc3 $1 {This is
good, since White is forced to take with the pawn.} 9. bxc3 Re8) 6... Bxc3+ 7.
Qxc3 (7. bxc3 $6 e5 $132) 7... b6 8. e3 (8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 11.
Qc2 Bb7 12. e3 {Here we have three ideas: ...h5, ...f5, and ...Ndf6.} h5 $1 $15
{works very well in this case. The threat of ...h4 forces a concession.} (12...
f5 {[%cal Yd8e7,Ye7f6,Ye8c8]}) (12... Ndf6 {[%cal Yd8e7,Ye8c8]}) 13. Bd3 f5) (
8. g3 Bb7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O a5 (10... c5 {is another acceptable continuation.}
11. dxc5 {One important rule: in these positions, we take back either with the
b-pawn or the knight. White is better after 11...dxc5.} bxc5 $11 (11... Nxc5
$11) (11... dxc5 12. Rd1 $16)) 11. b3 Be4 $1 $11 {We know this idea from
"Typical Strategies".}) 8... Bb7 9. Be2 O-O (9... a5 {is not a mistake, though
I would call it anti-positional. In general, we want to play on the kingside
and ...a5 creates a target on the queenside.} 10. b3 (10. b4 {can also be
played.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O Ne4 12. Qc2 f5 13. Bb2 Rf6 (13... Qe7 {--> see
model game 0-1 (71) Maiorov,N (2500)-Kovalenko,I (2684) Tallinn 2017.}) 14. d5
Rh6 $1 {An important rule: if d4-d5 comes with tempo, we always play ...Rh6.} (
{Against} 14... Rg6 15. Nd4 $14 {can be annoying.}) 15. Nd4 $2 {Here this is a
blunder.} Qh4 16. h3 Ng5 $1 $19 {[%cal Yg5h3] Black has a decisive attack.})
10. O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 f5 12. Ne1 (12. b4 Rf6 13. Ne1 Rh6 14. g3 Qe8 (14... Qg5
$36 15. Ng2 Ndf6)) (12. Nd2 Qh4 (12... Qg5 13. Bf3 Qg6) 13. Nxe4 fxe4 $1) 12...
Qh4 13. f3 Ng5) (5. e4 $6 {This seems to be premature! Now we play on the dark
squares!} c5 $3 (5... e5 $4 {would be logical if it weren't for} 6. Qa4+ Nc6 7.
d5 $16) 6. dxc5 (6. d5 $6 exd5 7. cxd5 O-O {[%cal Yf6e4]} 8. f3 Re8 $15 {
[%cal Yf6d5]}) 6... Bxc5 $1 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. h3 {Now I really like} e5 $132 {
Black has a perfect game. d5 is weak, but d4 is also weak.} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6
$2 Qxf6 11. Nd5 Qd8 $17 {The d5-knight will be exchanged and afterwards White
is left with a terrible bishop.}) (5. Bg5 Nbd7 $5 6. a3 (6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 (7.
Bxf6 Bxc3+ ({or} 7... Qxf6) ({but not} 7... Nxf6 $4 8. Qa4+ $18) 8. Qxc3 Nxf6
9. Nf3 b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O O-O $11 {We already achieved our goal: to reach
a good and playable position with many possibilities for both sides. For
example} 12. Rfd1 Ne4 {[%cal Yf7f5]} (12... Qe7 {[%cal Yc7c5]}) (12... a5))
7... b6 {I would like to delay castling for a while. If we play ...g5, ...Ne4,
and ...f5, it is possible that we can castle long.} 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 g5 10.
Bg3 Ne4 11. Qc2 Bb7 12. Ne2 (12. Nf3 h5 $1 13. d5 Ndc5 $15 {The threat of ...
h4 forces a concession from White.}) 12... Qe7 13. O-O-O O-O-O {and Black has
a good position. The h6-pawn is not weak - Black can always play ...h5 and ...
g4 or ...h4; sometimes also ...c5.} 14. f3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 g4 $5 16. e4 (16. f4
f5 17. Nc3 Nf6) 16... h5 {[%cal Yh5h4]}) 6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 h6 8. Bh4 g5 $3 {
THE COMPUTER ALWAYS LIKES THIS ...g5-Ne4 !} 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. Qc2 f5 (10... Ndf6
$1 11. e3 Bd7 12. Bd3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Qe7 14. O-O-O O-O-O $36 15. Ne2 h5) 11. e3
Ndf6 $3 {surprisingly, the best plan always seems to be Ne4-f5 Ndf6!! ....and
then NOT b6-Bb7....but Bd7!!-Bc6!!} 12. O-O-O Bd7 $3 13. Bd3 Qe7 14. f3 Nxg3
15. hxg3 O-O-O 16. Ne2 h5 $15) (5. e3 O-O $5 (5... c5 $5 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nf3
Nc6) 6. Bd3 (6. Nf3 b6 $132 (6... c5) (6... Re8 $5 7. Be2 e5 8. O-O e4 (8...
exd4 9. exd4 Bxc3 10. bxc3 Bg4) 9. Nd2 Bxc3 $5 (9... Bf5) 10. Qxc3 (10. bxc3
Bf5) 10... d5 $5 (10... c6 $132 11. b3 d5 12. Ba3 Bg4 (12... Bf5)) 11. cxd5
Nxd5 12. Qc2 Bf5 13. a3 Qg5 (13... Re6) (13... Nd7 $15))) (6. Bd2 Nbd7 $1 (6...
c5 $5 7. a3 (7. dxc5 Bxc5 $1) 7... Bxc3 $1 8. Bxc3 cxd4 $1 9. Bxd4 e5 (9... Nc6
10. Bc3) 10. Bc3 a5) 7. a3 (7. Nf3 b6 (7... e5)) 7... Bxc3 8. Bxc3 c5 $1 9. Nf3
b6 $1) 6... e5) (5. Bd2 {Now White wants to play a3 and take back on c3 with
the bishop. Then queen and bishop are placed very harmoniously. We need to
know what to do against this!} Nbd7 6. a3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 c5 8. dxc5 Nxc5 {
Experience shows us that we should not aim for a symmetrical position when our
opponent has the pair of bishops. Black has a playable position.}) 5... Bxc3+
6. Qxc3 Nbd7 $5 {I like to postpone castling for a while - this can be useful
if White plays an early Bg5, which will be answered by ...h6 Bh4 g5!} (6... Qe7
$5 {This takes us totally out of book - with a playable position!} 7. g3 Bd7 8.
Bg2 Bc6 {--> see model game 0-1 (41) Short,N (2698)-Torre,E (2469) Istanbul
2012.}) 7. f3 $5 (7. Nf3 b6 8. Bg5 $6 (8. g3 Bb7 9. Bg2 c5 $3 {This move is
very good - Black gets a nice position.} (9... O-O 10. O-O a5 11. b3 Be4 12.
Bb2 Qb8 $132 {[%cal Yb6b5]} (12... h6 $132) (12... c6 $5 {[%cal Yb6b5,Yd6d5]}))
10. O-O Rc8 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 d5 $11 (12... cxd4 13. Qxd4 Nc5 14. Qe3 e5 $5
$13)) (8. e3 Bb7 9. b3 (9. b4 a5 $132 10. b5 $6 O-O {The inclusion of ...a5
and b5 is always in Black's favour since White's pawns become less flexible.
For instance: if he pushes d4-d5 in the future, then Black gets a great square
on c5!}) 9... Ne4 10. Qc2 f5 11. Bb2 O-O $132 12. Be2 Qe7 13. O-O Rf6 $1 {
with nice attacking chances.} 14. d5 Rh6 $1 15. g3 c5 $5 $132) (8. b3 Bb7 9.
Bb2 Qe7 10. e3 O-O 11. Be2 Ne4 12. Qc2 f5 13. O-O Rf6 (13... c5 $5) 14. d5 (14.
c5 Bd5 15. Ne1 Rh6 16. cxd6 (16. cxb6 Nxb6 $132) 16... Qxd6 $1 $132) 14... Rh6
