{A nice effort by myself and a good strategic achievement!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Bd2 O-O (6... c5 $1 {is also quite good. I
was a little afraid of} 7. Nb5 {but then} Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 (8. Nxd2 O-O) 8... Ne4
$15 {is fine.}) 7. a3 {When I see Bd2 AND a3, I am ready to take on c3 and
play ...c5!} (7. g3 $5 {We have two good moves:} e5 $5 (7... b6) 8. Bg2 Re8 9.
O-O Bxc3 ({but not} 9... e4 $2 10. Nxe4 $16 {[%csl Rb4]}) 10. Bxc3 e4 $15 {
Typical light-square strategy.} 11. Nd2 Qe7 12. e3 d5 $1 13. cxd5 (13. b3 c6
14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Rac1 Nf8 16. Bb2 Ne6 17. f3 exf3 18. Bxf3 Ng5) 13... Nb6 $15
14. Rae1 Bf5 15. Qb3 Qd7 16. Nc4 Nxc4 17. Qxc4 Nxd5 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Gd5,Gd7,Ge8,
Gf5] This position perfectly defines the light-square strategy. Black has
realized the optimal scenario and is much better.} 18. Rc1 c6 19. Rfe1 Bh3 20.
Bh1 Qf5) (7. O-O-O $2 {This is too risky:} Bxc3 $3 8. Bxc3 b5 $3 {This gambit
works perfectly against 0-0-0!} 9. cxb5 Bb7 $3 10. e3 a6 $17) (7. e3 b6 (7...
c5) (7... e5) 8. Be2 Bb7 9. O-O Qe7 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Ne4 12. Nd2 f5 13.
Nxe4 fxe4 $1 {The e4-pawn cuts the board in half - we get great attacking
chances on the kingside.} (13... Bxe4 {is not good.} 14. Qd2 {White will soon
play f3.}) 14. b4 Qh4 15. a4 Rf6 16. a5 Raf8 $19) (7. e4 e5 {is the logical
answer.} 8. a3 $2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 exd4 10. Bxd4 Nxe4 {wins a pawn.}) 7... Bxc3 8.
Bxc3 c5 $1 9. dxc5 (9. e4 cxd4 $1 10. Bxd4 e5 $1 11. Bc3 Nc5 12. Nd2 Bd7 $3 13.
b3 (13. b4 Na4) 13... Bc6 $1 {Black has no time to pressurize our pawn on d6.}
14. f3 a5 15. Be2 Qb6 $17) (9. e3 b6 $1 10. Be2 (10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Be2 (11. Ng5
e5) 11... Bb7 (11... Nce4 $5 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 $11) 12. O-O Rc8 $132) (10. Bd3 Bb7
11. O-O (11. dxc5 $6 Nxc5 $3 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Bxh7+ Kh8 14. Bd3 Qxb2 $1 $17 {
[%csl Ra3,Rc4]}) 11... Bxf3 $3 12. gxf3 cxd4 13. exd4 $2 (13. Bxd4 Rc8 $36)
13... Rc8 $3 $17 14. Kh1 d5 15. b3 g6 16. Rg1 Nh5 17. Qd2 Qf6 $17) 10... Bb7
11. O-O Qe7 12. Rfd1 Rac8 13. dxc5 Nxc5 $1 {This is perfectly possible as
taking on f6 turns out to be favourable for Black:} (13... bxc5 14. Nd2 $5) ({
For sure, we don't go for the symmetrical position.} 13... dxc5 14. Nd2 $16)
14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Rxd6 $2 Be4 $1 16. Qc3 Qxc3 17. bxc3 $15 {Black has more
than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 9... Nxc5 10. g3 $6 {A very slow move.
Also, the light-squared bishop will be missed on the queenside!} (10. e3 Bd7 $5
({Black can also simply eliminate the c3-bishop.} 10... Nce4 11. Bd3 (11. Bxf6
Nxf6 $11) 11... Nxc3 12. Qxc3 b6 13. O-O Bb7 14. Nd2 Rc8) 11. b3 Rc8 $36) (10.
Ng5 $6 e5) 10... Bd7 $3 $15 11. Nd2 (11. b4 $2 Na4 $1 12. Bb2 Rc8 $17) ({After
} 11. b3 $6 {Black takes over the initiative with} b5 $1 $17 12. cxb5 Rc8 $3
13. Qb2 e5 14. Bg2 Nce4 $17) 11... Bc6 $1 12. f3 Na4 $5 (12... Rc8 $15) 13. Bd4
(13. e4 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 d5 $17) (13. Bg2 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Rc8 15. O-O d5 $17 {
We have a symmetrical position in which Black is much more active. Also the
move f3 is quite harmful.} 16. cxd5 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Bxd5) 13... e5 $1 14. Bf2 e4
$1 {A very nice sacrifice!} 15. Bg2 Re8 $1 16. fxe4 Nc5 $1 17. O-O Nfxe4 $1 18.
Nxe4 Bxe4 $1 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 20. Bd4 $15 {I evaluated this position in my favour.
The d6-pawn is not really weak - I have a permanent knight on e4 protecting it.
And I already saw that my queen has good prospects on the light squares.} Qd7
$1 21. Qd3 a6 $5 22. Rf4 Qe6 $1 23. Raf1 f6 24. e3 $2 {This is a huge
positional blunder. The bishop gets stuck on d4.} Rac8 $1 25. b3 d5 $1 26. cxd5
(26. c5 Nxc5 27. Bxc5 Rxc5) 26... Qxd5 27. Rf5 Qd7 (27... Re5 $3 $19 {
Stockfish!!}) 28. Qd1 Qe6 $1 29. Qd3 Rc6 $1 30. b4 Rec8 $1 $19 31. R5f4 Ng5 $1
32. Rh4 Rc1 $1 33. Bc5 $2 Nf3+ $19 {Very accurate play by me!} 0-1

