{In this lecture, we start dealing with the so-called Rubinstein Variation
arising after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {Statistically speaking,
this is White's most popular option against Nimzo-Indian Defence. Our
repertoire against it will be based on} O-O {There are 4 systems for White
here: a) Bd3 with Nge2 b) Bd3 with Nf3 which is called the Huebner variation c)
Bd3 with a3 (or a3 first and then Bd3) d) Nge2 without Bd3 You are strongly
advised to start with the theory and then carefullu study the model games.} *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "Norrkoeping"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "NIMZO 4.e3  FULL THEORY"]
[Black "ALL   LINES"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E47"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[EventDate "2010.04.02"]
[EventType "swiss"]
[EventRounds "8"]
[EventCountry "SWE"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O {There are 4 systems for White here: a)
Bd3 with Nge2 b) Bd3 with Nf3 which is called the Huebner variation c) Bd3
with a3 (or a3 first and then Bd3) d) Nge2 without Bd3} (4... c5 5. Nge2 $1 {
is annoying, if we want to play for a win!}) 5. Bd3 $1 {SUPER SOS ...!!!!!
This is the most flexible move for White.} (5. Nge2 $5 d5 $1 {THE MOST SIMPLE!}
(5... Re8 $1 {is another good line, intending to put the bishop back on f8.}) (
5... c6 $1 6. a3 Ba5 {Also a good line, now there's a square on c7 for the
bishop.}) (5... d6 $2 {This is passive and loses the bishop pair without
compensation:} 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 $16) (5... c5 $2 {This is a mistake against
Nge2!} 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 $14 {White has simply won the bishop pair.}) 6. a3 (
6. cxd5 $6 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 $1 $15 {After exchanging on d5 prematurely, White
has no c4-c5 resource against this move! If} 8. Nb5 Be7 {, we will kick the
knight back with a tempo.}) (6. g3 $2 dxc4 7. a3 Qd5 8. Rg1 Ba5) 6... Be7 (6...
Bd6 7. c5 $132) 7. cxd5 (7. Nf4 c6 {Preparing the ...Nbd7, ...dxc4, ...e5
freeing operation in the centre.} 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. O-O dxc4 10. Bxc4 e5 $1 11.
Nfe2 (11. dxe5 $6 Nxe5 12. Be2 Bf5 $15 13. f3 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bc2 $3 15. Rd2 Bb3)
11... exd4 (11... Bd6 $132) 12. exd4 Nb6 $132) (7. Ng3 c5 $1 {The problem with
Ng3 is that it doesn't support the d4 point and it doesn't put pressure on d5
either! (Unlike Nf4!)} 8. dxc5 (8. Be2 $6 cxd4 9. exd4 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nc6 11.
Be3 b6 12. O-O Bb7 $15 {In this typical isolated pawn position, White cannot
afford to have such a bad knight on g3!!!}) (8. cxd5 cxd4 $3 9. exd4 Nxd5 10.
Be2 Nc6 $15) 8... dxc4 $1 (8... Bxc5 $5 9. b4 Be7 $132) 9. Qxd8 (9. Bxc4 Qxd1+
10. Nxd1 Bxc5 $15) 9... Rxd8 10. Bxc4 Bxc5 11. O-O b6 $1 $15 12. b4 Be7 13. Bb2
Bb7 14. Rfd1 Nbd7 $1) 7... exd5 (7... Nxd5) 8. Nf4 (8. Ng3 c6 $1 ({We can
choose ...c5 against the knight on g3 as well:} 8... c5 $1 9. Be2 cxd4 10. exd4
Nc6 11. O-O Be6 $132) 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Nbd7 {Black calmly develops, one of
the setups is ...Nf8, ...Bd6. ...g6 is a viable idea for the future, the main
point being the ...h5-h4 push, and not putting the bishop on g7!} (10... g6 $6
{Played immediately, this move allows} 11. f4 $3 $36 {, which can be dangerous.
} (11. f3 $6 {, on the other hand, would allow Black to demonstrate one of his
main ideas:} c5 $3 {The pawn on e3 has been seriously weakened, so Black
changes the gear to target it.} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Re1 Nc6 $15) 11... c5 12. f5)
11. Nf5 (11. Bd2 Nf8 12. Qc2 (12. f3 c5) 12... Bd6 $132) 11... Bf8 $132) (8. g3
$2 {Simply a bad move! Although it has been played several times!... watch
this wonderful ...Nbd7-Nb6-a5-c5 plan!.. and I very much like the ...Bd7!!
move later!!} Nbd7 $3 (8... a5 9. Bg2 c6 10. O-O Na6 $132 11. f3 c5 $3 $15) 9.
Bg2 Nb6 $3 10. O-O Re8 $15 (10... a5 $15) (10... c6 11. f3 c5 $1) 11. b3 (11.
f3 $6 c5 $1 12. b3 Bd7 $3 {stoping Na4 forever!} (12... Be6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14.
Nd4 Nc8 15. Na4) 13. dxc5 (13. g4 h6 $1 14. Bd2 Rc8 (14... a5 15. a4 c4 $17)
15. Ng3 Bd6 $17) 13... Bxc5 $17 14. Nd4 a6 (14... Rc8 $6 15. Qd3 a6 16. Bb2) (
14... Nc8 $3 15. Qd3 Ne7 $1 16. Bd2 Rc8 17. Kh1 Nc6 $1 $17 (17... Ng6 $3 $17
18. f4 Ne7 $3)) 15. g4 Bc6 16. g5 Nfd7 17. h4 f6 18. gxf6 Nxf6) 11... a5 $1 (
11... c6 $1 12. f3 Be6 $2 (12... c5 $1 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nd4) 13. e4 dxe4 14.
fxe4 c5 15. d5 Bd7 16. e5) 12. f3 c5 $1 (12... a4 $2 {A very instructive
mistake!} 13. b4 $1 c6 14. e4 $14 dxe4 $1 (14... Nc4 $2 15. e5 Nd7 16. f4 $16)
15. fxe4 $14 Bg4) 13. a4 (13. e4 dxe4 14. fxe4 cxd4) (13. Bd2 Bd7) 13... Bd7 $1
14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Nd4 Nc8 $3 (15... Rc8 $5 16. Qd3 Na8 $1 17. Bd2 Nc7 18. Rae1
Na6 $15) 16. Qd3 Qb6 17. Nce2 Ne7 $1 18. Bd2 Nc6 $1 $17 (18... Ng6 $1 $17 19.
f4 $2 (19. Rad1 h5 20. h4 Ne5 21. Qb1) 19... Ne7 $1 $17) 19. Rad1 Re7 (19...
Nb4 $17) 20. Bc1 Rae8 $17 21. Kh1 h6 $1 {prophylactic play... against a sudden
g3-g4!} (21... Nb4 22. Qb1 h5 $17) 22. Qc3 Rc8 23. Qd3 Rce8 24. Qc3 Rc8 (24...
Bd6 $1 25. Nb5 Bb8 $17 (25... Be5)) 25. Qd3 Ra8 (25... Nb4 $17)) 8... c6 9. Bd3
Na6 $3 (9... Bd6 $5 {See the game Mastrovasilis, A-Papaioannou}) 10. O-O (10.
Bxa6 $6 {Now the light squares are too weak for White to hope for an advantage!
} bxa6 11. O-O a5 $1 $36 (11... Rb8 $1 $36)) 10... Nc7 11. f3 (11. Bd2 Ne6 12.
Nxe6 Bxe6 13. f3 $5 (13. Rc1 Bd6 $1 $36) 13... Rc8 $1 (13... c5) ({Swiercz} 
13... g6 $5 14. Be1 Nh5 15. Bf2 f5 $132) 14. Be1 (14. b4 Bd6) 14... g6 15. Bg3
(15. Bh4 Nh5 (15... c5 $132) 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 $132) 15... Nh5) (11. Qc2 Ne6 12.
Nxe6 Bxe6 13. Bd2 Re8 14. h3 $6 (14. f3 c5 $15) 14... Bd6 $15) 11... Ne6 12.
Nfe2 Re8 (12... a5 $5 13. Bd2 b5 $132) 13. Kh1 c5 $132 14. Bd2 Bd7 15. Be1 cxd4
16. exd4 (16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. exd4 Bc6 18. Bh4 Nh5 $3 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. f4 Nf6
$15 (20... g6 $15 21. Qf3 Qe3)) 16... g6 $1 {SUPER SOS!... IT SEEMS THAT THIS .
..g6! MOVE, FOLLOWED BY ...Nh5 IDEAS IS THE WAY TO PLAY AGAINST THE Bd2-Be1
IDEAS!!} 17. Qd2 $5 $132 {˝-˝ ,M/Civitanova Marche ITA 2015/[} (17. Bh4 Bc6
18. Rc1 Nh5 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 $15 20. f4 f5 $3 $15)) (5. Nf3 {HUEBNER VARIATION !!}
c5 $1 (5... Bxc3+ $5 {This is also very good... remember: WHEN YOU SEE Nf3,
you can take on c3 and double White's pawns!} 6. bxc3 d6 7. Bd3 Qe7 8. O-O e5
9. e4 c5 $132 10. Bg5 (10. d5 Nbd7 11. Re1 Re8 12. Nd2 Nf8 13. Nf1 Ng6) 10...
Nbd7 (10... h6 $1 11. Bh4 Nbd7 12. Re1 Re8 13. Qc2 Nf8) 11. Nh4 $1) 6. Bd3 (6.
a3 $2 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. Bd3 Nc6) 6... Nc6 7. O-O (7. Bd2 cxd4 $1 8. exd4 d5
$1 9. cxd5 exd5 $5 (9... Nxd5 $5 10. O-O Be7)) 7... Bxc3 $1 {Generally in the
Nimzo, when you see a Nf3 move it is quite possible to capture on c3 by
yourself... doubling White's c-pawns... and continue wth ...c5-d6-Nc6!-e5
ideas!} 8. bxc3 d6 9. e4 (9. Nd2 b6 $132 (9... e5 $132 10. Ne4 Re8 (10... Qe7))
) 9... e5 10. d5 (10. dxc5 dxc5) (10. Bg5 $6 cxd4 11. cxd4 Bg4 $15 {White's
centre becomes to shaky and Black gets an attractive game.}) 10... Ne7 {
AND NOW... IF WHITE DOESN'T DO ANYTHING, OUR PLAN IS ...h6!-Nh7! and ...f5!}
11. Nh4 $1 (11. Rb1 h6 $1 12. Nd2 Nh7 13. Re1 b6 14. f3 f5 $15 15. exf5 (15.
Qc2 $4 f4 $19 16. a4 a5 17. Nf1 g5 18. Bd2 Ng6 19. Re2 h5 20. Rf2 Nf6 $19))
11... Ng6 $3 {This is the best! White is not given time for Qf3.} (11... h6 $5
12. Qf3 $1 {This is the whole problem with 11...h6} (12. f4 Ng6 $3 {The great
Fischer idea, which he used in a similar position against Spassky!} 13. Nxg6
fxg6 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Be3 b6 16. a4 a5) (12. f3 Ng6 $1 13. Nf5 Nf4 $3 (13...
Nh7 14. Rb1 b6 15. Be3 Ne7 $132) 14. Bxf4 $2 exf4 15. Qd2 Bxf5 $3 16. exf5 Nh5
$1 $17 17. Rfe1 Qf6 18. Re2 Rfe8 19. Rae1 Kf8 20. Qb2 b6 21. Qb5 Rxe2 22. Rxe2
Qd8 23. Qc6 Rc8 24. Qb7 Rc7 25. Qa6 Nf6 $19) 12... Ng6 13. Nf5 $16 {Black is
left in a passive position without couunterplay.}) 12. Nf5 (12. Nxg6 fxg6 $1 {
Playing on the newly open f-file next:} 13. f3 Nh5 $1 $15 14. g3 Bh3 15. Rf2
Rf7 16. Be3 Qe7 17. Qd2 Raf8 $17) 12... Nf4 $132 13. Bc2 (13. Bxf4 $2 exf4 14.
Qf3 g5 $3 $17 15. h4 Nd7 $3 (15... Bxf5 $3 16. exf5 h6 $17)) 13... g6 14. Nh6+
(14. Ng3 $2 Kh8 $3 15. Ne2 (15. f3 Rg8 16. a4 h5 17. Nh1 g5 $17) 15... g5 $17)
(14. Ne3 Kh8 {Preparing an attack with ...Rg8 and ...g5.} 15. Kh1 Qe7 16. f3
Rg8 17. g3 Nh3 $36) 14... Kh8 15. g3 Nh3+ (15... N4h5) 16. Kh1 Ng8 17. Nxg8
Rxg8 18. f4 exf4 19. gxf4 Qh4 $132) (5. a3 $5 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 $1 {In this
line we have very good play... BUT WE NEED TO MEMORIZE THE VARIATIONS!!} 7. Bd3
(7. Rb1 $5 {this is an interesting waiting move... White wants to see how we
will develop our pieces, if we will go for ...b6 or ...d6, and then he wants
to decide about the placement of the knight on g1! I suggest 7...h6! as a
clever and useful waiting move!} h6 $5 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Ne2 (9. h4 $6 {
Grischuk-Praggnanandhaa} d5 $1 10. cxd5 Qxd5 $36 11. Nf3 c4 12. Bc2 Ne4 13. Bb2
b6) (9. Nf3 $6 {with the knight on f3 , the ...d6-e5 plan is the most
effective!} d6 $1 10. O-O e5 $36) 9... b6 10. e4 Ba6 $132 11. O-O d6 12. f4 Na5
$5 (12... cxd4 $5 13. cxd4 Rc8 $132) 13. e5 Nh7 14. Qc2 f5 $132) 7... Nc6 8.
Ne2 (8. Nf3 $2 {SUPER SOS !!!! thats a Hubner with a tempo down for white! (a3)
} d6 $3 9. O-O e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. e4 h6 $3 12. Nd2 Nh7 $3 13. f4 $2 (13. Qc2 f5
14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Ne4 Qd7 $1 (15... Nf6 16. Nxc5) 16. Bd2 Nf6 17. Rae1 Nxe4 18.
Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Qf5 20. Qxf5 Nxf5 21. f3 g5 $15 {later in the engame i may
go Na5 or Nc8-Nb6 !!}) 13... exf4 14. Rxf4 Ng6 15. Rf1 Ne5) 8... b6 9. e4 Ne8
$3 {SUPER SOS!!... WHEN YOU SEE e3-e4, PLAY ...Ne8!! to avoid Bg5!!} (9... Ba6
$2 10. Bg5 $16 h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Na5 13. O-O Bxc4 14. f4 Bxd3 15. Qxd3) 10.
O-O (10. e5 $5 d6 $1 {Breaking White's far-advanced centre should be our
priority in similar situations.} 11. f4 {Maybe not the best, but the only
truly logical follow-up. If White allows his centre to break, Black just gets
an easy practical edge.} Qh4+ $3 12. g3 Qh5 {With our queen on the kingside,
our king will not come into danger any time soon.} 13. Be4 (13. O-O Bb7 $17)
13... Bb7 14. O-O Na5 $17 {White is left with weaknesses only.} 15. Bxb7 (15.
d5 Nxc4) 15... Nxb7 16. exd6 Nexd6) (10. Be3 $6 Ba6 $1 {We sacrifice the
c5-pawn because we can easily win the c4-pawn back and White ends up with a
damaged strcuture. This makes the whole Be3 idea not great for White.} 11. dxc5
Ne5 $15 12. cxb6 axb6 13. O-O Nd6 $15 (13... Bxc4 $15)) (10. f4 $6 f5) 10...
Ba6 11. f4 (11. Be3 $6 Nd6 $3 12. dxc5 Nxc4 $15) (11. e5 d6 $15 12. Bf4 (12. f4
Na5 $15 (12... g6 $132)) 12... dxe5 13. dxe5 Na5) (11. Qa4 Na5 12. dxc5 Qc7 $1
$15) (11. Ng3 Na5 12. f4 Bxc4 13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. f5 f6 $15) 11... f5 $1 (11...
Na5 $6 12. f5 $3 {starts a tremendous attack that we want to avoid:} Bxc4 13.
f6 $3 {This is the spectacular point.} Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Nxf6 15. Bg5 d6 16. Bxf6
gxf6 17. Ng3 $16) 12. exf5 (12. Ng3 g6 $1 {We are seemingly weakening the
dark-squares in our camp, but White's bishop doesn't really have acces to them.
} 13. Be3 (13. d5 Na5 14. Qe2 (14. dxe6 $2 {This is a terrible structural
transformation for White.} dxe6 $17) 14... Rf7 $132 {The more restrained
option, retaining good chances.} ({We can also go for the c4-pawn right away:} 
14... Nd6 15. e5 Ndxc4 16. d6 b5 $132 {This is a very complex position. White
definitely has some compensation for the pawn, but objectively the position
may be somewhat better for Black. It's certainly playable for us.}) 15. e5 Bb7)
13... cxd4 14. cxd4 d5 15. cxd5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 fxe4 17. Qxe4 (17. Nxe4 Qxd5 $132
18. Rad1 Rd8 19. Rfe1 Ng7) 17... Qxd5 18. Qxd5 exd5 $132 19. Rac1 (19. f5 Nd6
20. fxg6 hxg6) 19... Rc8 20. f5 Nd6 21. fxg6 hxg6 22. Rxf8+ Kxf8 23. h4 $6 {
Jussupow-Karpov 1993} (23. Ne2 $11) 23... Nc4 24. Bg5 Nxd4 $15) (12. d5 $2 {
[%emt 0:00:01]} exd5 $1 $17 13. cxd5 (13. exd5 Na5 14. Ng3 Nd6 $19) 13... Bxd3
14. Qxd3 fxe4 15. Qxe4 Nd6 16. Qc2 Na5 $17 17. Ng3 Qf6 18. f5 Rae8 19. Bf4 Nb5
20. Rac1 Nxa3 21. Qa4 N3c4 22. Qxd7 Qf7 23. Qb5 Qxd5 24. f6 Qc6 25. Qxc6 Nxc6
26. fxg7 Kxg7 27. Nh5+ Kg6 28. g4 N6e5 29. Bxe5 Nxe5 30. Nf4+ Rxf4 31. Rxf4 Nd3
32. Rcf1 Nxf4 33. Rxf4 a5 34. h4 Ra8 35. g5 a4 36. Rf6+ Kh5 37. Kf2 Kxh4 38. g6
hxg6 39. Rxg6 a3 40. Rg1 a2 41. Ra1 Kg4 42. Ke3 Kf5 43. Kd3 Ke5 44. Kc4 Ke4 45.
Kb3 b5 46. Kc2 Ke3 47. Re1+ Kf2 48. Ra1 Ke2 {0-1 Estremera Panos,S-Meshkovs,N/
Stockholm SWE 2019}) (12. e5 Na5 $15) 12... exf5 13. Ng3 g6 14. dxc5 (14. Be3
d6 $15) 14... bxc5 15. Be3 d6 16. Re1 $1 (16. Bxf5 $2 {This tactic in fact
falls for a trap that was deliberatley set by Black.} gxf5 17. Qd5+ Rf7 18.
Qxc6 Bb7 (18... Bxc4 $2 19. Rfe1 Qc8 20. Qf3 $16) 19. Qa4 h5 $3 $132 {The
whole point is that White's pieces are ineffective now while Black develops a
strong attack supported by his powerful bishop on the long diagonal. White's
extra pawn is irrelevant.} 20. Nxh5 $2 (20. Qc2 Qf6 $1 $19 (20... Ng7 $17 21.
Rfd1 Qe7 22. Nf1 h4 $17) 21. Bf2 h4 22. Ne2 Qg6) (20. Nh1 Rg7 21. g3 Qe7 22.
Rfe1 Qe4 {0-1 Manukyan,S-Zhigalko,S/chess.com INT 2020}) 20... Qh4 21. Ng3 Rh7
$17) 16... Nf6 $132 17. Bf2 (17. Qa4 Bb7 18. Rab1 Qd7 $15) 17... Qd7 {
Carlsen-Nakamura 2020} 18. Nf1 Na5 $1 (18... Rae8 $132 19. Ne3 Bb7) 19. Bh4
Rae8 $1 20. Ne3 Bb7 $1 $132) 5... c5 $1 6. Nge2 (6. Nf3 {transposes to the
Huebner variation} Nc6 7. O-O (7. d5 Ne7 8. e4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 d6 10. O-O e5) (7.
Bd2 d5 (7... cxd4 8. exd4 d5)) 7... Bxc3 {This trade is a good idea with the
white knight on f3, which would be better placed on e2 in the resulting
positions.} 8. bxc3 d6 9. e4 (9. Rb1 e5 10. d5 Ne7 {We should only put the
knight on a5 when it's established theory or we see that we will be able to
capture the c4-pawn.} 11. e4 h6 $132 {Intending ...Nh7 and ...f5 with a great
game.} ({We cannot omit ...h6:} 11... Ne8 12. Qc2 f5 $2 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Ng5
$16 {White exploits the g5-square to reach e6 to our detriment.})) (9. Nd2 e5
$132) 9... e5 $132 {See 5.Nf3 for the further line}) (6. a3 {transposes}) 6...
cxd4 $1 7. exd4 d5 $1 8. cxd5 (8. O-O $6 dxc4 $1 9. Bxc4 Nc6 {Practice has
shown that the bishop is misplaced on c4 and this version of the IQP position
is not promising for White.} 10. a3 {There's a wide choice of good options for
Black here.} (10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Be7 $132) (10. d5 {White may want a draw, but
it's not so trivial for him to simplify like this:} Na5 $1 {10...exd5 is ok if
we're fine with a draw.} 11. Qd3 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 Bxc3 13. Nxc3 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5
15. Qd4 Be6 $11 {Objectively it's equal, but a pawn is still a pawn and we can
push for a win.}) 10... Bd6 $5 (10... Be7 $132 11. Be3 b6 12. Rc1 (12. d5 Ne5
$11) 12... Bb7 $11) (10... Bxc3 $1 $132 11. bxc3 b6 $3 12. Bg5 Bb7 (12... h6
13. Bh4) 13. Bd3 h6 14. Bh4 Na5 $11 {Black has nice light-square control and
White is not able to break it:} 15. c4 $2 {This try fails tactically.} Rc8 16.
Rc1 g5 17. Bg3 Nxc4 $1 $17 {With ...Qd5 at the end.}) 11. h3 (11. Bg5 $2 Bxh2+)
11... h6 $1 12. Be3 Ne7 {We take control of the d5-square. We can continue
with ...b6 or ...Bd7-c6, already with some advantage in each case.} 13. Qd2 (
13. Rc1 b6 $15 (13... Bd7 14. Qd2 Bc6 $15)) 13... b6 $15 (13... Bd7 $15) 14.
Rac1 Bb7 $132) (8. c5 $6 {This advance can be strategically dangerous for
Black if White has a substantial lead in development and can support the pawn
choice. This is not the case here.} b6 9. cxb6 {Both recaptures are promising.}
Qxb6 (9... axb6 $5 10. O-O Ba6 $1 $15) 10. O-O Ba6 $15 {The only thing White
has achieved is a worse pawn structure.}) 8... Qxd5 $1 {This is more rare, but
at least as good as 8...Nxd5!} 9. O-O Qd7 $1 $132 {SUGGESTED BY Sielecki...
EXTREMELY RARE BUT VERY GOOD!} (9... Qh5 $1 $132 {THIS IS ALSO INTERESTING...
CHECK THE GAME SESSION} 10. Be3 (10. Ne4 Nxe4 $5 (10... Nbd7 $5) 11. Bxe4 Nc6
12. Be3 Rd8 $132) 10... Nc6 11. h3 (11. Rc1 Bd6 12. h3 (12. Ng3 Qxd1 13. Rfxd1
Nb4 14. Bb1 Bd7 $11 (14... Bxg3 15. hxg3 Bd7 $11)) 12... Nb4 13. Bb1 Bd7 14.
Qd2 Nbd5 $11 (14... Bc6 $11)) 11... Rd8 12. Qc2 Bd6 13. a3 Bd7 $36 {We always
have some latent potential to attack White's king in these positions.}) (9...
Qd8 $5 $132 {ALSO SIMPLE AND VERY GOOD!} 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Rc1 Bd7 $1 {The right
setup: the bishop goes to c6 and the knight to d7!} 12. Bb1 Bc6 13. Qd3 Nbd7
14. Rcd1 Re8 15. Rfe1 Nf8 $36 {White's attack is well contained. Black has the
slightly better chances thanks to the long-term anti-IQP prospects.}) 10. Bc2
$5 (10. Bg5 Be7 11. Rc1 Nc6 12. Qd2 (12. a3 Rd8 13. Qc2 h6 14. Be3 b6 15. Rfd1
Bb7 $36) 12... Nb4 $132 13. Bb1 (13. Bb5 Qd8 $36) 13... b6 $1 14. Rfe1 Bb7 $15)
10... Nc6 11. Qd3 (11. Bg5 $6 {IT'S UNBELIEVABLE, BUT THIS NATURAL MOVE IS A
MISTAKE!!} Be7 $1 $15 {The lack of accuracy of White's last move is revealed
by the fact that now, once the bishop vacated b4, Qd3 is met by ...Nb4!} 12.
Qd2 (12. Qd3 $2 Nb4 $17) (12. a3 Rd8 $1 $15) 12... b6 13. Rad1 Ba6 $15 {
Black has ways to press against the d4-pawn., e.g.} 14. Rfe1 Rfd8) 11... e5 $1
{Black solves all potential opening problems by liquidating in the centre.} (
11... Be7 $5 {This is playable, but a bit more risky.} 12. a3 Rd8 13. Rd1 (13.
Bg5 $2 Nxd4 $3 $17) 13... g6 (13... Qe8 $5 $132 14. Bg5 Ne5 15. Qg3 Ng6) 14.
Bg5 b6 $132 (14... Ng4 $5 $132)) 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 f5 $132 14. Qh4 Nxd4 $11
(14... Be7 $5 $11 {should be also fine.}) 15. Nxd4 Qxd4 $11 {All White can get
is activity suffcient to compensate for the pawn deficit, but Black is not in
any danger.} *

