{A very good game in the Huebner variation... although the proposed move order
in the theory part is different (we play 4...0-0! not 4...c5), the plans are
still valid 100 per cent!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 (4. Nf3 Bxc3+ 5.
bxc3 d6) 4... c5 (4... O-O 5. Nf3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6) 5. Bd3
Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O e5 9. d5 Ne7 10. Nd2 (10. e4 h6 $1 {Here in
addition to the typical ...Nh7, ...f5 plan, Black has the idea of ...g5 since
he hasn't castled yet. White's attempt to disrupt this idea may prove rather
counterporductive:} 11. Nh4 g5 12. Qf3 Nfg8 {This is only temporary
passiveness.} 13. Nf5 Nxf5 14. exf5 Nf6 $15 {White runs a big strategical risk.
Black has the idea of getting his king to c7 and blocking all avenues of
possible play by White, e.g.} 15. Bd2 Kd7 16. Rab1 Kc7 17. a4 a5 18. Rb5 b6 19.
Rfb1 Rb8 $17 {White finds himself in a complete dead end.}) 10... O-O 11. f4 $6
{A bad choice.} (11. e4 h6 {Of course, the usual plan with ...Nh7, ...f5.} 12.
Re1 Nh7 13. f3 f5 14. exf5 (14. Qc2 $4 f4 $19 {Allowing the ...f4 push is a
terrible choice for White, who becomes strategically (and objectively, in
engine evaluation terms) lost. Black gets a free hand for the typical
KID-style kingside attack.}) 14... Bxf5 15. Ne4 Nf6 {White struggles to even
maintain equality, e.g.} 16. Be3 $6 ({The engine suggests} 16. Ng3 $11) 16...
Nxe4 17. fxe4 Bd7 $15 {Something has started going wrong for White. The bishop
pair is irrelevant in this position defined by White's rigid and flawed pawn
structure.}) 11... exf4 (11... Nd7 $2 {This would be the same mistake that
White commits if he allows ...f5-f4.} 12. f5 $1 {White gets a free reign on
the kingside, e.g.} f6 13. e4 Rf7 14. g4 Nf8 15. h4 Bd7 16. Nf3 $18 {and it
will take some time, but Black is essentialy finished.}) 12. exf4 {it is very
important to keep the blocked on f5 ...preventing the Bc1 from being activated
!} Bf5 $1 {Keeping the light-squared blockade, not allowing White to push
f4-f5.} 13. Qc2 ({The energetic play with} 13. Bxf5 Nxf5 14. g4 {would be
desirable for White, but it's not possible on account of} Ne3 $19) 13... Qd7 $1
{A simple and strong move that keeps the blockade intact.} 14. Nf3 ({If} 14. h3
{Black again simply keeps the blockade with} h5) 14... Rae8 15. Bd2 ({If} 15.
Nh4 {I intended to play} g6 $3 (15... Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qg4 $1 {is also strong.})
16. Nxf5 Nxf5 17. h3 h5 $17 {and taking on f5 theoretically damages Black's
structure, but Black gets too much control over the ligth squares in the
centre and completely dominates:} ({Or, even better,} 17... Ne3 $1 18. Bxe3
Rxe3 $19 {with White in fact lost due to his weaknesses, e.g.} 19. f5 g5 ({or} 
19... Qe7)) 18. Bxf5 $2 Qxf5 19. Qxf5 gxf5 $19 {...Re4-Rxc4 is inevitable.})
15... Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qf5 17. Qb1 Qd7 18. Qd3 Nf5 19. Rae1 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 g6 21.
h3 h5 $17 {Black has a total blockade and he begins to exploit White's
weaknesses soon, without Whit being able to find any counterplay.} 22. Be3 Re8
23. Bf2 Rxe1+ 24. Nxe1 Qe8 25. Qb1 Qe2 26. Nf3 Ne4 27. Qe1 Qxe1+ 28. Bxe1 Ne3
29. Ng5 Nxg5 30. fxg5 Nxc4 31. Bg3 Kf8 32. Kf2 Ke7 33. Kf3 b5 34. Bf4 Nb6 35.
Ke4 Nd7 36. Kf3 f5 37. gxf6+ Nxf6 38. Bg5 Kf7 39. Bf4 Ke7 40. Bg5 a6 41. a3 a5
42. Ke2 Kf7 43. Bf4 Nxd5 44. Bxd6 Nxc3+ 45. Kd3 Na4 46. Ke2 Ke6 47. Bc7 Kd5 48.
Bxa5 Ke4 0-1

