{[%evp 0,104,25,29,23,15,10,10,20,19,23,15,15,15,31,31,30,21,33,33,24,-7,3,-10,
30,29,29,24,26,35,59,40,34,40,62,62,57,57,81,47,66,35,69,9,13,13,43,0,-1,-8,
-12,-44,-13,-15,3,2,22,20,42,-18,13,20,32,9,38,13,24,10,10,10,-1,-34,-13,-55,
-38,-59,-30,-85,-91,-192,-203,-150,-158,-158,-141,-150,-73,-73,-88,-86,-17,-32,
-100,-99,-103,-107,-99,-103,-107,-103,-113,-115,-138,-120,-187,-203,-228] This
is not our main move order, but still the game remains very illustrative.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 ({There are other move orders where Black can
postpone the short castle and it's possible to experiment with them, e.g.} 4.
Nf3 d6 5. e3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. O-O e5 {(instead of 8...0-0)}) 4...
c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e4 e5 9. d5 Ne7 10. g3 h6 11. Nh4 g5
12. Ng2 Qa5 $1 {Black goes for a continuation that allows him to castle long
quickly.} 13. Qb3 Bh3 14. O-O O-O-O 15. Rb1 ({Black's main plan no matter what
is to tuck the bishop back on c8, firmly protecting b7 and start gradually
attacking on the kingside, e.g.} 15. Re1 Kb8 16. Rb1 Bc8 17. Ne3 Rdg8 $15 {
Black has great perspectives, similarly to the game.}) 15... Qc7 16. f3 Kb8 17.
Rf2 Rhg8 18. Ne3 Bc8 $1 {Parking the bishop!} 19. Kf1 {White tries to evacuate
his king from the danger zone.} Rdf8 20. Ke1 Ne8 {Black is ready for ...f5.}
21. Nf5 $6 {Unfortunately for White, this only magnifies his problems.} Nxf5
22. exf5 f6 $6 (22... Nf6 $1 $17 {was more active and better here, but Black
still manages to win an instructive game despite commiting a significant
inaccuracy at this point.}) 23. g4 Rh8 24. Be3 h5 $17 {White has 2 very bad
bishops!} 25. Bf1 Rf7 26. h3 Qd7 27. Kd2 Nc7 28. a4 Re7 29. Re1 Na8 30. a5 Qd8
31. Qa3 Rhh7 32. Rb1 b6 $3 {Amazing plan!... Black can afford to open his own
king because white has inactive bishops!!} 33. Bd3 Rb7 $3 34. axb6 Nxb6 $19 {
White is strategically busted. Black carries out his plan of exchanging all of
the major pieces and winning the minor piece endgame thanks to the c4-weakness
and the passed a-pawn.} 35. Ra1 Qh8 36. Kc2 hxg4 37. hxg4 Bd7 38. Qa2 Rh2 39.
Kd2 Rxf2+ 40. Bxf2 Qh2 41. Ke2 Na4 42. Qd2 Be8 43. Rb1 Rxb1 44. Bxb1 Qf4 45.
Bd3 Qxd2+ 46. Kxd2 Nb6 47. Kc1 Ba4 48. Bc2 Bd7 49. Bd3 Kc7 50. Kb2 Bc8 51. Kb3
Ba6 52. Be3 Nxd5 {A classic in the Huebner variation by Huebner himself!} 0-1

