{[%evp 0,68,30,29,27,15,15,20,20,20,17,8,8,14,29,29,32,33,27,27,27,34,31,34,34,
28,37,40,36,36,19,51,51,59,107,51,48,18,18,23,26,32,45,61,65,61,76,57,64,53,47,
55,43,44,74,76,61,0,0,-12,-12,0,0,0,0,-90,-61,-115,-44,-1177,-1149] Not a
perfect game, but it nicely illustrates some opening subtleties.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O ({There is
a problem with the move order played by Black in this game:} 8. e4 $1 {
(planning e5)} e5 9. d5 $16 {The knight can't reach c6 and e7. Suddenly the
situation isn't good for Black!}) 8... Nc6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 (10. Be3 b6 11. h3
h6) 10... Ne7 11. Nh4 $5 {Against any other move by White, our plan is ...
h6!-Nh7! and ...f5.} (11. Nd2 h6 12. Qc2 Nh7 13. Re1 f5) (11. Ne1 Ne8 $1 {
only here we ned to go f5 even faster!} 12. Nc2 (12. g4 $5 Nf6 13. h3 h6 14.
Ng2 Nh7 $132 {with a nice idea if White doesn't play f4:} 15. Qc2 g5 $3 $15 {
The mutual kingside blockade is in Black's favour.}) 12... f5) 11... Ng6 $1 12.
Nf5 Nf4 13. Bc2 g6 14. Nh6+ (14. Ne3 Kh8) 14... Kg7 ({I recommend} 14... Kh8 $1
{in the theory part. After the text the game goes a bit astray for Black, but
he eventually turns in around in the endgame.}) 15. g3 Nh3+ 16. Kg2 Ng8 17.
Nxg8 Rxg8 18. f4 exf4 19. gxf4 Qh4 20. Qf3 h5 21. e5 Qg4+ 22. Qxg4 hxg4 23.
exd6 Bf5 24. Bxf5 gxf5 25. Re1 Rgd8 26. Re7 b6 27. a4 Rxd6 28. a5 Kf6 29. Re5
Ng5 30. axb6 Rxb6 31. Re2 Ne4 32. Be3 a5 33. Rea2 a4 34. Rb2 Rxb2+ 0-1

