{[%evp 0,60,14,26,28,-6,6,6,33,29,35,35,30,30,43,43,43,43,42,26,22,24,23,23,31,
30,39,-11,21,25,32,-19,28,-4,-23,-11,-17,-17,-7,-36,-49,-39,-29,-29,-23,-88,
-104,-144,-146,-210,-96,-181,-105,-364,-364,-890,-1003,-1732,-627,-1890,-29988,
-29995,-984] This game is an excellent demonstration of Black's ideas in the
Huebner Variation and shows how a single mistake in the opening by White can
leave him in long lasting problems.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nc3 c5
5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O Nc6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nh4 Ng6
12. Nf5 Nf4 13. Be3 $2 {An unfortunate move.} g6 $17 14. Ng3 g5 ({There was an
even better option:} 14... Ng4 $1 {With threats of ...Nxe3 and ...Qh4.} 15. h3
Nxe3 16. fxe3 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Kg7 $17 {Black will slowly but surely prepare ...
f5 while White has no active plan.}) 15. Nf5 Kh8 16. g3 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Bxf5 18.
exf5 Rg8 $15 {The position is still very hard for White. The structure only
gives him weaknesses.} 19. Kh1 $2 {Now it becomes even worse.} (19. h3 $15 {
intending g4 was the lesser evil.}) 19... Qd7 20. f3 {Forced since ...e4 was a
threat. But now Black opens the game for his rook:} g4 21. fxg4 Rxg4 $17 {
White's position is objectively close to lost and practically almost hopeless,
as he has no play of his own. White collapses in a matter of a few moves.} 22.
Qe2 Rag8 23. Rab1 b6 24. Bh6 Ne4 25. Qe3 f6 26. Rb5 Qf7 27. Rg1 Qh5 28. Bf4
Qxf5 29. Bh6 Rxg3 30. Rxg3 Nxg3+ 0-1

