-196,-245,-322,-333,-348,-415,-462,-489,-444,-444,-443,-458,-488,-494,-547]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3
d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nh4 Ng6 12. Nf5 Nf4 13. Bc2 g6 14. Ne3 Kh8 15. f3
Rg8 16. g3 Nh3+ 17. Kh1 g5 18. Ng4 h5 19. Nf2 Nh7 20. Be3 Qf6 21. Nxh3 Bxh3 22.
Rf2 Qg6 23. Qe2 f5 24. exf5 Bxf5 25. Bxf5 Qxf5 26. Qc2 {Black has conducted
the game very well and has the typical edge that Black can hope for if
everything goes according to the plan. Now both choices, exchanging the queens
or not, are promising in their own way.} Qh3 (26... Qxc2 27. Rxc2 Rgf8 28. Rf1
Rae8 29. Kg2 Kg7 $15 {is an example of a tough endgame for White, despite the
engine's modest evaluation. Black always has the idea of bringing the knight
all the way across the board to hit c4. The game takes a similar course after
the eventual queen trade.}) 27. Rg1 Raf8 28. Qc1 Rf7 29. Qf1 Qf5 30. Qb1 Rgf8
31. Qxf5 Rxf5 32. Rgf1 Kg7 33. Kg2 Kg6 34. h3 Re8 35. Re1 Rf7 36. h4 gxh4 37.
gxh4 Kf5 38. Kh3 Rg8 39. Bh6 (39. Rff1 Rfg7 40. Re2 {was required, and White
is objectively able to hold, but with the black rooks controlling the g-file,
it all still looks suspicious.} (40. Rg1 $2 {leads to a clearly won endgame
for Black:} Rxg1 41. Rxg1 Rxg1 42. Bxg1 Nf6 43. a4 Nd7 44. a5 Kg6 45. Kg2 a6
$19 {Followed by ...b6. There are other ways to win as well, Black's advantage
is overwheliming.})) 39... Rg6 40. f4 $2 {Allowing the e-pawn to become
Black's crucial asset. White had to retreat the bishop to preserve saving
chances.} e4 41. Bg5 Rg8 42. Rfe2 Re8 43. Re3 Nf8 44. Bh6 Nd7 45. Rg3 Rh7 46.
Bg7 Re7 47. Reg1 e3 48. Rg6 e2 49. Re6 Rhxg7 50. Rxe2 Rxe2 51. Rxg7 Nf6 52.
