1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8.
bxc3 d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nh4 Ng6 12. Nxg6 fxg6 13. a4 ({It might be a
practically wise choice, although a tough pill to swallow for White at the
same time, to play} 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 $15 {White is worse, but he
doesn't run the risk of losing the c4-pawn without the black knight to attack
it, or the risk of his dark-squared bishop becoming really bad, since he has
exchanged it. Black will try to advance on the kingside.}) 13... Nh5 14. a5 Nf4
15. f3 $6 ({After the preferable} 15. Bxf4 exf4 $5 {is the maximalist choice,
but White will not let Black block the e5-square if he knows what he's doing:}
(15... Rxf4 $15 {is a simple small edge.}) 16. e5 $1 dxe5 17. Re1 Qd6 18. Qe2
Re8 19. Be4 $11 {With sufficient compensation for the pawn for White, as the
protected passed pawn on d5 is a long-term asset.}) 15... g5 {Now Black starts
taking full control over the position.} 16. Re1 h5 17. Bf1 (17. Bxf4 gxf4 $17 {
with the plan of ...g5-g4 is also one-sided.}) 17... Qf6 18. Ra2 Rb8 19. Rf2 g4
20. g3 Nh3+ 21. Bxh3 gxh3 $17 {White remains much worse in the
opposite-coloured bishops position due to his weaknesses and lesser king
safety. Black won a really clean game considering it was blitz.} 22. Ref1 Qg6
23. Qd3 b6 24. axb6 axb6 25. f4 Bg4 26. f5 Qf6 27. Ra2 Ra8 28. Rxa8 Rxa8 29.
Qc2 Qf7 30. Bg5 Kh7 31. f6 Qg6 32. Bh4 gxf6 33. Rxf6 Ra1+ 34. Kf2 Qg7 35. Rxd6
Rh1 36. Ke3 Re1+ 37. Kd3 Rf1 38. Qd2 Qf8 39. Qg5 Qf3+ 40. Kc2 Qd1+ 41. Kb2 Qa1+
42. Kc2 Qa2+ 43. Kd3 Rf3+ 44. Qe3 Rxe3+ 45. Kxe3 Qe2# 0-1

