{Let's take again a look at the starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defence -
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {In this lecture, we are going to examine the
continuations 4.g3, 4.Nf3, 4.f3, and 4.Qb3. All these lines (especially 4.f3)
should be taken very seriously. In this lecture, you will see how to
neutralize them without having to spend a lot of time on learning theory.
After checking the theoretical section, make sure to go through all the model
games. This is how you will get feeling of the arising positions.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "chess.com INT"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.g3  & 4.Nf3"]
[Black "Theory"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E20"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[EventDate "2020.12.15"]
[EventType "swiss (blitz)"]
[EventRounds "10"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 (4. Nf3 {White is delaying his decision to
choose a setup.} Bxc3+ $1 5. bxc3 d6 6. g3 b6 $1 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 $132 {
The 4.Nf3 move order (instead of 4.g3) allows this possibility to play a well
timed b6!-Bb7! This position is very rare but very good for Black!}) 4... O-O
$1 {A very good system for Black which works perfectly after both 4.g3 and 4.
Nf3.} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ $1 {you can also capture on c3 before any other
move as well.} 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O (8. Qd3 $1 {planning Nd2 e4.} Rb8 $1 {this is
better than 8...e5 9.Nd2} 9. Nd2 (9. Bg5 $6 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. O-O e5 12.
Rab1 Bf5 $1 13. e4 Bg4 $15 {Black has a stable edge because of better Bishop})
9... Qd7 $1 {A very strong move!} 10. O-O b6 11. e4 (11. Ne4 $2 Nxe4 12. Bxe4
f5 13. Bg2 Ba6 {planning Na5-Qa4 next.}) (11. Nb3 $1 Ba6 $5 12. Bg5 Ne8 $1 {
Important move to memorize.} 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Be7 Bxc4 15. Qc2 Nf6 16. Bxf8
Rxf8 17. Rfe1 d5 18. Nd2 Ne4 $132 {Black got compensation for the sacrificed
exchange.}) (11. g4 Na5 12. g5 Nh5 13. Nb3 Ba6 14. Nxa5 bxa5 15. Qf3 g6 $15 {
Threatning Bxc4 and planning ...f6 soon.}) (11. Ba3 Ba6 12. Rfd1 Rfd8 13. e4
Na5 $15 {with usual plans, Black is favourable.}) 11... Ba6 12. f4 Na5 $1 {
planning Qa4-c5.}) 8... e5 $1 $36 {Black atleast has an equal position.} 9. Qc2
(9. c5 e4 $1 10. Nd2 d5 $1 11. c4 Bf5 $1 {with a nice light square strategy!}
12. Rb1 b6 $15 13. cxd5 Qxd5 {Black is clearly ahead in developement.}) (9. Rb1
e4 10. Ne1 h6 $1 $132 {we dont want to exchange the Bc1  !!}) 9... Re8 $1 {
stopping e2-e4} 10. Bg5 (10. Rd1 $2 {falls to} e4 11. Ne1 h6 $17 {when Black
clearly dominates White.}) 10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 $15 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "chess.com INT"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.f3 c5!"]
[Black "Theory"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E20"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[EventDate "2021.03.09"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 {White must push d5.  What
happens after e3 instead? That's actually a very bad move as it leads to d5!
when White's pawn on f3 makes no sense.} O-O 6. e4 {Remmember if White plays
a3 respond with Ba5!} Re8 $1 {A very interesting move order, setting up
various positional and tactical traps before we take exd5. Sooner or later we
will surely play d6 & b5.} 7. Nge2 $1 {the main move} (7. dxe6 $2 {A very bad
strategic decision!} dxe6 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 $15 {We may plan Nc6-Nd4 or Bxc3 and
take advantage of the doubled pawns.} 9. Nge2 Nc6 10. Be3 b6 $17 {Planning Ba6,
Black has a very good position.}) (7. Bg5 $4 {Probably the worst possible
choice for White, Black wins immediately.} exd5 8. Bxf6 (8. cxd5 Nxe4 $3 $19 {
Black wins!}) 8... Qxf6 9. cxd5 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Kf2 d6 12. Ne2 Qf6 13.
Ng3 g6 $19 {Black has one extra pawn for no compensation.}) (7. Nh3 $6 {
Planning Nf2-Be2, 0-0 & f4. However in this position White has tactical
problems.} d6 $1 8. Nf2 b5 $3 $132 {Important break to memorize!} 9. Be3 (9.
dxe6 $2 Bxe6 10. cxb5 d5 $36 {White's King in the center decides the game
itself.}) (9. Bd2 $6 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 b4 $3 {A very typical idea, Black wins a
free pawn soon.}) (9. Be2 $6 {Planning short castle.} bxc4 10. Bxc4 exd5 11.
Bxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Be6 $3 $17 {Black is almost winning after this very
important move. White's queen get's trapped if he takes on a8.}) 9... Bb7 $3 {
Keeping the tension.} 10. dxe6 Rxe6 11. Be2 bxc4 12. O-O d5 $132 {and the
fireworks favour Black.}) (7. Bd2 {playable but not threatning.} d6 8. a3 (8.
Nge2 a6 {important prepratory move in case direct ...b5 doesn't work.} 9. Ng3
exd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 11. Be2 Nf8 {planning b5, Rb8 we are on the better side.})
8... Ba5 {It doesn't make sense to capture on c3 now as we are not doubling
White's pawns.} 9. Nge2 a6 {planning b5!} 10. Nf4 (10. Ng3 b5 {with usual
plans.}) 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Nbd7 12. Be2 Ne5 13. h4 c4 {planning b5 to create
counterplay.}) (7. Kf2 $6 {is not as bad as it looks!} d6 {keeping the tension.
} 8. Nge2 (8. Bd3 $2 exd5 9. cxd5 (9. exd5 Nbd7 $17 {with similar plans.}) 9...
Nbd7 $17 10. Nge2 Ne5 11. Bf4 c4 $17 {Black has a huge advantage.}) 8... exd5
9. cxd5 h5 $1 $132 {with a comfortable position.}) (7. Be2 $6 d6 $1 {as we
don't see anything clear, it is best to wait.} 8. Bd2 a6 9. a4 (9. a3 Ba5 $36
10. a4 b5 {with huge complications!}) 9... Qe7 10. Qc2 h6 $132 {stopping Bg5,
Black soon is planning for ...b5}) (7. a3 Ba5 {very important! We don't
capture on c3 in such positions.}) (7. Bd3 $2 {looks very natural but yet its
very bad!} exd5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {as it simply drops a pawn.} 9. Nge2 Qh4+ $3 10.
g3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qf6 12. O-O Bxc3 $17 {Black simply has more material with no
compensation.}) 7... d6 (7... exd5 {is also possible.} 8. cxd5 d6 {planning
a6-b5-Nbd7-Nf8, play this only if you are lazy!}) 8. a3 (8. Kf2 {it may look
strange, but this is also possible.} exd5 9. cxd5 Nbd7 10. g4 Nxg4+ 11. fxg4
Qh4+ {when Black has a better position in Ghimpu,S-Stepanencu,N/Mamaia ROU 2021
}) (8. Bg5 {planning for longcastle soon.} h6 9. Bh4 exd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 11. Qc2
b5 12. O-O-O Bxc3 13. Nxc3 b4 {Black has sufficent attack in Kobalia,
M-Kacheishvili,G/Linares 2001/CBM 081}) (8. Bf4 {falls into ...Nh5 plans.} exd5
9. cxd5 Nh5 10. Bd2 Nd7 11. Qc2 Ne5 12. O-O-O Nc4 {0-1 (42) Richter,M-Ghaem
Maghami,E/Berlin 2015/CBM 168 Extra}) 8... Ba5 9. Ng3 (9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Nf4 Nc6
11. Nfd5 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Nxe4 {once again this typical sac saves the day!} 13.
fxe4 Qh4+ {0-1 (23) Miedema,D-Parligras,M/Iasi 2014/CBM 160 Extra}) (9. Bg5
exd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 11. Ng3 Nxe4 {very important sacrfice in these variations.}
12. Bxd8 Nxc3+ 13. Kd2 Nxd1+ 14. Bxa5 Ne3 15. Re1 Nxf1+ 16. Rhxf1 Re5 {0-1 (43)
Petrisor,A-Parligras,M/Sarata Monteoru 2011/CBM 140 Extra}) (9. Kf2 exd5 10.
cxd5 Nbd7 11. g4 Ne5 12. Ng3 c4 13. g5 Nfd7 14. f4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Nd3+ 16. Bxd3
cxd3 17. Qxd3 Nc5 {0-1 (30) Sarkar,J-Lenderman,A/Philadelphia 2011/CBM 143
Extra}) 9... b5 10. Kf2 (10. Bd2 bxc4 11. Bxc4 Ba6 {with equal play as in
½-½ (41) Palliser,R-Jones,V/Sheffield 2011/CBM 143 Extra}) 10... bxc4 11.
Bxc4 Ba6 {Black has a playable position.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2023.07.11"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Qb3 c5!"]
[Black "Theory"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E23"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[EventDate "2023.07.11"]
[EventType "swiss (blitz)"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 c5 $1 {Usually, when you see the move Qb3
in various versions and in many different move orders of the nimzo , you
should answer with a7-a5! However, in this particular move order, the best way
to meet 4.Qb3 is with 4...c5!} 5. dxc5 Nc6 $1 6. Nf3 (6. a3 {falls into} Nd4 7.
Qd1 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc6 {and the tripled pawns will quickly fall.}) 6... Ne4 $1
7. Bd2 Nxd2 $1 8. Nxd2 Bxc5 9. e3 O-O 10. Be2 b6 {we reach an unclear position
with chances for both sides. The pair of bishops is always an asset for Black
though!} 11. O-O Bb7 12. Rfd1 (12. Nde4 Be7 13. Rfd1 $132 {with counterplay.})
12... f5 $1 (12... Rc8 {is also possible} 13. Nde4 Be7 14. Nd6 Na5 $1 {
pressurizing c4 pawn next.}) 13. Bf3 (13. Na4 Rb8 $132 {safeguarding the
b7-Bishop.}) 13... Qe7 $15 14. Na4 Bd6 15. Rac1 (15. c5 Bxc5 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 $17
{Black is material up.}) 15... Rab8 16. g3 g5 $17 {with good attacking
prospects.} *

