{[%evp 0,28,20,20,20,6,8,8,22,-7,12,-62,-17,-63,-30,-30,-24,-47,-28,-7,-2,1,6,
6,39,37,19,16,32,4,10]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {This is the
so-called Leningrad variation of the Nimzo, it used to be quite popular in the
previous century! We have 2 good ways to play against it : with a closed
center approach (d6-e5) and with an open center (d6-ed5) I choose the latter
approach because it is active and good, without the need to know much theory!}
h6 (4... c5 $5 {is also possible.}) 5. Bh4 c5 (5... Bxc3+ {is also possible.}
6. bxc3 d6 {planning b6-Bb7-Nbd7}) 6. d5 (6. e3 $5 {If you wish to avoid the
e3 lines, please play 4... c5 first instead of 4... h6} Qa5 7. Rc1 cxd4 8. exd4
Ne4 {attacking on c3.} 9. Qc2 d5 10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Ba3 12. Rb1 dxc4 13.
Bxc4 O-O 14. Nf3 Bd6 $132 {with huge counterplay.}) 6... exd5 {exd5 is the
modern way of handling this position. There is nothing wrong with the old main
lines of the Bxc3-d6-e5 closed center !} (6... d6 $5 {is a good alternative.}
7. e3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 e5 $132 {with plans like Nbd7-Nf8-Ng6.}) 7. cxd5 d6 8. e3 (
8. f3 $6 {this takes us to the lines of the Nimzo 4.f3-c5 (in a bad version of
them!) where Black also has a great game!} O-O 9. e4 Re8 10. Bb5 $1 {only move
!} (10. Nge2 $2 Nbd7 $17 {The problem for White is that he cannot move his e2
Knight, While Black can easily develop.}) (10. Bd3 $4 {falls into sneaky
tactics.} Nxe4 $19) (10. Qc2 Nbd7 $3 {planning Ne5} 11. Nge2 Ne5 12. O-O-O Bd7
$17 {with b5-Qa5 to follow up.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Nge2 a6 12. Bxd7 Bxd7 13. O-O
b5 14. Rc1 Qe7 15. Kh1 Ba5 $3 {Planning Bd8-Qf8-Nh5 and f5!}) 8... O-O $1 {
Black has a really great game in various different ways.} (8... g5 $1 {a very
interesting (and very forced) continuation, leading to unclear play} 9. Bg3 (9.
Bb5+ $2 Ke7 $3 10. Bg3 Qa5) 9... h5 10. h4 $1 (10. f3 $6 h4 11. Bf2 Nbd7 $15) (
10. h3 $6 Ne4 11. Nge2 Nd7 $36 12. Qc2 Ndf6) 10... Ne4 {with huge
complications on the board.}) 9. Bd3 {This Bd3-Nge2 line looks a bit better
than 9.Nf3, but Black is still doing very well with the Nbd7-Ne5-Ng6! plan.} (
9. Nf3 a6 $1 {planning b5. There are many other playable moves too} 10. a4 Bf5
$1 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nbd7 13. O-O Re8 $15 {with a good position.}) 9...
Nbd7 10. Nge2 Ne5 11. O-O (11. Bc2 $6 {we weren't really threatening Nxd3, so
we would go Ng6 anyway.} Ng6 12. Bg3 (12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. O-O g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 {
Planning Qf6 and attack!}) 12... Nh5 $1 13. O-O (13. a3 Bxc3+ $3 14. Nxc3 Nxg3
15. hxg3 Ne5 $36 {this g4 square is weak ! ..so in fact, e5 is practically a
strong square, because white can hardly ever play f4} 16. O-O Bd7 17. a4 Ng4 {
planning Qg5-Qh5.}) 13... f5 14. a3 Bxc3 $5 {with Nxg3 and Qf6 to follow.})
11... Ng6 $1 (11... Bd7 $1 {is an interesting waiting move because White is
not really threatening Ne4} 12. Ne4 $6 {leads to} g5) 12. Bg3 (12. Bxg6 $6 fxg6
$15 {Black has a small but clear advantage.}) 12... Nh5 $5 13. Qc2 (13. f4 Nxg3
14. Nxg3 f5 $1 {stopping e4 & f5 plans immediately.} 15. Qc2 Nh4 $132 {soon we
will plan Ba5-Qe8-Bd8 and Bf6}) 13... f5 14. f4 Bd7 $132 {Black can possibly
plan Qe8-Rc8 or Qf6-Rce8 with good play over the weak pawns.} *

