{[%evp 0,22,20,20,20,6,7,7,22,-36,-10,-24,-16,-21,69,58,70,69,65,53,73,56,79,
-1,51]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 (4. a3 {risky but tricky as well!}
Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O 6. f3 (6. g3 $5 d6 7. Bg2 Qe7 8. Nf3 e5 9. O-O e4 $15 10. Nd2
Re8) (6. Nf3 d6 7. Bg5 (7. e3 $2 {that is , in fact, a Huebner variation with
a tempo less for White (the move a3)}) 7... h6 8. Bh4 Qe7 9. e3 e5 {with usual
play like e3 variations}) (6. e3 $5 c5 {We convert into e3 lines.} 7. Bd3 Nc6
8. Ne2 b6 {transposes into the Nakamura-Volokitin game.}) 6... Ne8 $1) 4... O-O
5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne8 $1 {and with this very clever move , it is very
possible that in the end we will transpose to the e3-a3 variation, with one
irrelevant extra move for white (f3). Please note that f3 is not at all
important because White anyway has to play f4, so either f2-f4 or f3-f4 ..its
the same!} 7. e4 c5 $1 {now , in most cases we will transpose to the e3-Bd3-a3
nimzo ...and if white tries too hard to avoid it, h may end up worse!} (7...
Qh4+ $5 {this is another clever way to get out of book. We lose some time with
the queen, but provoking g3 is good for Black!} 8. g3 Qe7 9. Bd3 d6 10. Ne2 c5
11. h4 $5 e5 12. g4 (12. d5 f5) 12... exd4 $1 {white was threatening to block
everything with d4-d5!} (12... Nc6 $4 13. d5 Na5 14. Ng3 $18)) 8. Bd3 $5 (8. d5
$6 d6 (8... Qh4+ $5 9. g3 Qf6) 9. Bd3 Qh4+ $1 10. g3 Qf6 (10... Qe7) 11. Qc2 (
11. Bd2 Nd7 12. f4 b5 $15) 11... Nd7 12. f4 b5 $3 $17) (8. Ne2 b6 $1 {we are
ready once again to transpose to the e3-Bd3-a3 lines.}) (8. f4 $5 {an
interesting try and a totally new position!!} cxd4 9. cxd4 b5 $3 {what a move
by Mr.Computer} 10. cxb5 (10. Nf3 $6 {fails to} bxc4 11. Bxc4 d5 12. Bd3 Nd6
13. e5 Ne4 $15 {When Black's pieces are more active and have high prospects.})
(10. c5 $2 d6 $17 {opening up the center with quick development to follow.})
10... Bb7 11. e5 a6 $1 {Once again, we wish to open the position as quickly as
possible, to seize the initiative.} 12. bxa6 Nxa6 13. Nf3 Bxf3 $3 14. Qxf3 Nb4
{and the tactics favour us.}) (8. dxc5 $6 Qa5 9. Ne2 Na6 $15) 8... Nc6 9. Ne2 (
9. Be3 b6 $1 10. dxc5 Ne5 $3 $15) 9... b6 10. O-O Ba6 11. f4 f5 {as promised,
it transposes to the e3-Bd3-a3 Nimzo !} *

