1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {White can play Bd2 in various Nimzo
positions. The main idea is to get out of book and simply play chess.} (4. e3
O-O 5. Bd2 b6 $1 6. Nge2 (6. Nf3 Bb7 7. Bd3 c5 {transposes}) (6. a3 Bxc3 7.
Bxc3 Ne4 8. Ne2 Qh4 $1 {with good play.}) 6... Bb7 7. a3 Be7 $1 {When White
connects his knights with Nge2 in the nimzo after a3, we usually go back Be7}
8. Ng3 d5 $132 {...c5 is also possible.}) 4... O-O 5. a3 (5. Nf3 b6 $1 {
with typical nimzo-queen's indian play !} (5... d5 $5 6. a3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 dxc4)
6. a3 (6. e3 Bb7 7. Bd3 c5 8. O-O (8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxd4 10. exd4 d5 $132)
8... cxd4 9. exd4 d5 $132 10. cxd5 Nxd5) 6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. e3
Nxc3 (9... f5 $5) 10. Qxc3 d6) 5... Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Ne4 $1 {The Capablanca
method! First we give the bishop for the knight and then we give the knight
for the bishop!!} 7. Rc1 Nxc3 8. Rxc3 d6 $132 {planning ...e5 with natural
play.} *

